# [0.18.5] - 2026-04-28

## Security Fix - SOT Out-of-Bounds Tile Index Heap Info Leak (CVE-2026-TBD)

**Critical security update**: Fixed heap out-of-bounds access in tile-part dispatch that could be exploited via crafted SOT markers in malformed JPEG 2000 codestreams.

### Security Impact
- **CVE-2026-TBD**: Heap out-of-bounds read/write in `j2k_tile::add_tile_part()` reached via unchecked `Isot` (SOT tile index)
- **Attack vectors**: Crafted J2K/JP2 files; reachable in the JPIP server's startup codestream load (`PacketLocator::build`) and in every decoder entry point (`invoke()`, `invoke_line_based()`, `invoke_line_based_stream()`, `invoke_line_based_predecoded()`)
- **Confirmed primitive**: Server-surviving heap information leak — heap pointers written by `add_tile_part()` into memory adjacent to the `tileSet` allocation can be reflected back to the client through later JPIP tile-header data-bin responses
- **Credit**: Vulnerability discovered and responsibly disclosed by KANG DAEUN (SANGMYUNG UNIVERSITY) and OH HAN GUEL (SANGMYUNG UNIVERSITY, @5asever40-a11y)

### Fix Details
- Added bounds check for `Isot` against `tileSet.size()` (i.e. `numTiles.x * numTiles.y`) at all four SOT-dispatch sites in `source/core/interface/decoder.cpp`
- Out-of-range tile indices now throw `std::exception()` with a diagnostic before any write through the offending pointer
- Verified under AddressSanitizer that the previously reported `heap-buffer-overflow` at `coding_units.cpp:3336` no longer triggers for the published PoCs (`poc_01_server_surviving_heap_info_leak_*.j2k`, `poc_02_server_heap_info_leak_*.j2k`)

### Migration Notes
- No API changes - existing valid inputs continue to work
- Malformed inputs with `Isot >= numTiles` are now rejected at parse time instead of silently corrupting heap memory

**Recommendation**: All users running JPIP servers or decoding untrusted JPEG 2000 content should upgrade to v0.18.5.

# [0.18.4] - 2026-04-27

## Security Fix - PPM Packet Header Heap Buffer Overflow (CVE-2026-TBD)

**Critical security update**: Fixed heap buffer overflow vulnerability in PPM packet header parsing that could be exploited via malformed JPEG 2000 codestreams.

### Security Impact
- **CVE-2026-TBD**: Heap buffer overflow in `j2k_codeblock::pass_length[128]` array
- **Attack vectors**: Malicious JPIP server responses, crafted J2K/JP2 files
- **Affected components**: JPIP server/client, decoder processing PPM markers
- **Credit**: Vulnerability discovered and responsibly disclosed by KANG DAEUN (SANGMYUNG UNIVERSITY) and OH HAN GUEL (SANGMYUNG UNIVERSITY, @5asever40-a11y)

### Fix Details
- Added `kMaxCodingPasses = 128` constant matching `pass_length` array size
- Implemented bounds checking in three vulnerable code paths:
  - General packet header parsing (`parse_packet_header`)
  - HT mode with secondary passes
  - Bypass mode with multiple segments
- Fail-fast security model: throws `std::exception()` when bounds would be exceeded
- Added security regression tests to prevent future occurrences

### Migration Notes
- No API changes - existing valid inputs continue to work
- Malformed inputs now properly rejected instead of causing undefined behavior
- Enhanced diagnostic output for debugging malformed codestreams

**Recommendation**: All users should upgrade immediately to v0.18.4, especially those processing untrusted JPEG 2000 content or running JPIP servers.

# [0.18.3] - 2026-04-22

## WASM decoder — SIMD pack paths for 16-bit and planar-u8 output

Two WASM-SIMD patches to the decoder wrapper, plus a CMake bug fix that
was causing the non-threaded `libopen_htj2k_simd` variant to silently
run scalar pack code.  Output is byte-exact with the previous builds
on every file we tested; the change is pure perf.

Measured on a 3840×2160 12-bit YCbCr codestream, Ryzen 9 9950X / Node 24:

| Config | Before | After | Speedup |
|---|---:|---:|---:|
| `libopen_htj2k_simd`, PPM output | 105.0 ms | 81.0 ms | 1.30× |
| `libopen_htj2k_mt_simd` 2T, PPM output | 63.8 ms | 42.1 ms | 1.52× |
| `libopen_htj2k_mt_simd` 4T, PPM output | 64.9 ms | 36.9 ms | 1.76× |
| `libopen_htj2k_simd`, planar-u8 output | 94.3 ms | 85.2 ms | 1.11× |
| `libopen_htj2k_mt_simd` 2T, planar-u8 output | 52.1 ms | 45.2 ms | 1.15× |
| `libopen_htj2k_mt_simd` 4T, planar-u8 output | 50.0 ms | 41.5 ms | 1.20× |

### WASM

* **`invoke_decoder_stream`** — new WASM-SIMD pack block for the
  `nc==3 && !subsampled && 16-bit big-endian` case (12–16 bpc RGB
  PPM output).  Processes 8 samples per iteration across R/G/B,
  writing 48 output bytes per three v128 stores via an i32→u16 narrow,
  per-pair byte-swap, and 3-way shuffle interleave.  The previous
  code took the scalar fallback here even on the simd variant, so
  this is the single biggest line-item in the stream-mode speedup.
* **`invoke_decoder_planar_u8`** — new WASM-SIMD rescale for the
  per-component inner loop (add DC-offset bias, right-shift for
  depths ≥ 8, left-shift for depths < 8, clamp to [0,255], narrow
  i32→u8, 16-byte store).  Used by `subprojects/rtp_demo.html` to
  upload three R8 textures per frame; previously scalar.
* **Byte-exact** against pre-patch output on all 137 `wasm_*`
  conformance tests, plus explicit plane-level md5 checks on
  8-bit 4:4:4, 12-bit 4:4:4, 12-bit 4:2:2, and 4-bit grayscale
  fixtures for the planar-u8 path (which has no conformance-test
  coverage).

### Build

* **Fixed** `libopen_htj2k_simd` target in `subprojects/CMakeLists.txt`
  missing `OPENHTJ2K_ENABLE_WASM_SIMD`.  The target was being compiled
  with `-msimd128` but without the macro, so every
  `#if defined(OPENHTJ2K_ENABLE_WASM_SIMD)` branch in `wrapper.cpp`
  (grayscale pack, 8-bit RGB pack, YCbCr→RGBA) was compiled out and
  the variant silently ran scalar wrapper code.  The mt_simd target
  had the define and was unaffected.
* **C++17** required for the subproject build — rtp_reassembly
  object libraries use `std::optional`.
* **Dropped** redundant `-s SHARED_MEMORY=1` from the MT link flags;
  `-pthread` implies it, and Emscripten 3.1.x rejected it as unknown.
* **New option** `OPENHTJ2K_WASM_PROFILE` (default `OFF`) passes
  `--profiling-funcs` to the Wasm linker so `node --cpu-prof` and
  `perf record --perf-basic-prof` resolve function names.  ~15% .wasm
  size overhead, zero runtime cost (verified: release vs profile
  builds are within run-to-run noise on both simd 1T and mt_simd 2T).

### CLI

* **`subprojects/open_htj2k_dec.mjs`** now calls `process.exit(0)` once
  the output file has been written.  On multi-threaded WASM builds
  (`-num_threads > 1`) Emscripten's pthreads layer keeps
  `worker_threads` workers parked waiting for a teardown signal that
  never comes, so the CLI appeared to hang indefinitely after a
  successful decode.  The decoded output was always correct; only the
  process lifetime was wrong.

### Tools

* `subprojects/wasm_bench.mjs` — new iteration-loop bench harness.
  Loads a chosen WASM variant once, runs N decode iterations, reports
  min/median/p95/mean wall-clock plus Msamples/s and fps.  Supports
  `--mode stream|planar_u8`, `--dump-planes <prefix>` for byte-exact
  regression-checking, and `--build-dir` for A/B between two build
  outputs.

### Documentation

* **`docs/wasm_bench.md`** — prerequisites, synopsis, full option
  table, worked examples (baseline throughput, thread sweep,
  RTP-demo-shaped planar-u8 path, byte-exact regression check), and a
  profiling section that covers both `node --cpu-prof` for
  single-threaded variants and `perf record --perf-basic-prof` for the
  multi-threaded variants (where `--cpu-prof` silently produces no
  output because Emscripten's pthread teardown bypasses Node's
  profile finalizer).  Linked from `docs/README.md` under a new
  "Developer tools" section.

# [0.18.2] - 2026-04-21

## JPIP gigapixel viewer — mid-decode paint on slow fetches

Third of the three small latency wins queued after v0.18.0's precinct
cache.  During a response that's taking a long time to download, show
the user whatever precincts have already arrived instead of holding
the viewport stale until the final byte lands.

Purely client-side (viewer JS only) — no server, WASM, or library
changes.  Gated on wall-clock elapsed so fast fetches (cache hits,
LAN round-trips) never trip it and don't pay the double-decode cost.

### Browser viewer

* **Mid-decode paint** fires at most once per response, after
  `?midPaintMs` elapsed, from inside the `_jpip_feed_stream` read
  loop.  It runs `jpip_end_frame_region` + `texSubImage2D` against
  the partial `DataBinSet` so the user sees a progress frame with
  whatever precincts have landed so far.
* **Final paint** at end-of-response is unchanged — re-decodes with
  the complete `DataBinSet` so the visible result is correct.
* Stats bar now reports `mid-paint=<N>ms` when the branch fires so
  the latency win is visible at a glance; `?debug=1` logs the same
  to the console.

### New URL parameter

* **`?midPaintMs=N`** — wall-clock threshold in milliseconds.
  Default `200`; set `0` to disable.  Chosen so the typical 1920
  full-res response on LAN (~50 ms) never triggers, but a
  multi-MB first-pan response over a home broadband link does.

### Cost model

Fast fetch (<200 ms): no mid-paint branch taken, no overhead.
Slow fetch (>200 ms): one extra `jpip_end_frame_region` call
(~20–50 ms CPU on a 1920 viewport) in exchange for seeing the
partial image 150–500 ms earlier on a slow link.  Final paint
always re-decodes so the on-screen result is correct.


# [0.18.1] - 2026-04-21

## JPIP gigapixel viewer — adjacent-viewport halo prefetch

Builds on v0.18.0's LRU precinct cache: after each successful render,
if the user holds still, prefetch a small halo of precincts just
outside the viewport so a short follow-up pan lands in the cache and
the per-pan fetch collapses to the 3-byte EOR.

Purely client-side (viewer JS only) — no server, WASM, or library
changes.  Gated by a user-driven idle period: continuous panning
never triggers the prefetch, so bandwidth cost is paid only when
the user actually pauses to examine the viewport.

### Browser viewer

* **After each successful render** `fetchView()` arms a 150 ms idle
  timer.  If the user doesn't interact by the time it fires, the
  viewer issues a `&rsiz=<halo>&model=…` fetch expanded by
  `?prefetchMargin` canvas pixels on each side, pipes the response
  through the WASM streaming parser, and skips the render (the
  bytes just fill the LRU cache).

* **`scheduleFetch()` cancels the pending prefetch** via
  `AbortController` and `clearTimeout` so a new user pan always
  pre-empts the halo.  In-flight halo bytes that already landed in
  the LRU stay useful; everything past the abort point is dropped.

### New URL parameters

* **`?prefetchMargin=N`** — halo width in canvas pixels, applied to
  all four sides.  Default `128`; `0` disables.  With the default
  64 MB LRU, a 128 px halo adds ~40% overhead to the first pan
  after load (fetching halo-exclusive precincts) and ≤15% on
  subsequent pans once previous halos overlap with the fresh one.

* **`?prefetchDelayMs=N`** — idle delay (ms) before the halo fires.
  Default `150`; short enough to overlap typical pause-and-examine
  behaviour, long enough that continuous panning never triggers it.

### Measured (1920×1920 asset, live server)

| Scenario | Response bytes |
|---|---|
| Main fetch (no cache) | 28863 |
| Halo fetch (no cache — worst case) | 37206 |
| Halo fetch (main's precincts cached) | **~10 KB of halo-exclusive precincts** |
| Halo fetch (everything cached) | 3 |


# [0.18.0] - 2026-04-21

## JPIP gigapixel viewer — client-side precinct LRU cache

The gigapixel viewer now tracks received precincts in the §C.9
`&model=` cache-model advertisement so the server skips redelivery
on subsequent pans.  On typical in-window pans this cuts per-request
wire bytes by 70–95%; on a fully-cached view-window the entire
response is the 3-byte EOR marker.

The feature is opt-in: the foveation demo intentionally decays its
periphery per frame and stays unchanged.

### Library

* **`DataBinSet::erase(class_id, in_class_id)`** (new).  Drops a
  bin's bytes and its `is_last` flag so a subsequent server re-send
  can legitimately re-fill it — this is the primitive the viewer's
  LRU uses to evict old precincts while keeping the DataBinSet
  consistent.

* **`CacheModel::unmark(class_id, in_class_id)`** (new).  Removes a
  previously-marked bin so the next `&model=` advertisement no
  longer claims the client holds it.

### WASM

Three new exports in `subprojects/src/jpip_wrapper.cpp`:

* `jpip_track_precincts_in_cache(ctx, enabled)` — toggle the LRU.
  When turned on, every complete precinct already in `ctx->set` is
  back-filled into the LRU + cache-model so the next request
  accurately reflects what the client holds.  Turning it off clears
  the LRU entirely.
* `jpip_set_precinct_cache_budget(ctx, lo, hi)` — 64-bit budget in
  bytes, split into lo/hi 32-bit halves for Emscripten's i32
  calling convention.  Default 64 MB.
* `jpip_get_precinct_cache_count(ctx)` — diagnostic: number of
  precinct bins currently in the LRU.

LRU semantics: insertion order = touch order (ties broken by last
touch), eviction evicts from the front, re-hits move-to-back.
Evictions remove the bin from both `ctx->set` (to make room + keep
`append()`-rejects-on-is_last happy) and from `client_cache` (so
the next `&model=` advertisement is accurate).

### Browser viewer

`subprojects/jpip_viewer.html` enables the LRU after
`jpip_create_context()`.  New URL parameter:

* **`?precinctCacheMB=`** — budget in megabytes; default `64`, pass
  `0` to disable.  `&model=` assembly continues to range-compress
  (`P0-99,P101,P103-...`) so dense hits stay short even on 40k+
  precinct asset.

The foveation demo (`jpip_demo.html`) is intentionally left with
precinct tracking off so per-frame decay of the peripheral cones
continues to work as before.

### Migrating from v0.17.x

External callers that call `jpip_add_response` / `jpip_feed_stream`
directly are unchanged — precinct tracking stays off until the
caller opts in.  The only observable difference in the viewer is
that subsequent pans on the same region see 70–95% smaller
responses and proportionally smaller server-side + client-side
decode work.


# [0.17.2] - 2026-04-21

## JPIP server — Content-Length is now the default, chunked is opt-in

Interop fix for reference interactive JPIP clients whose HTTP/1.1
parsers do not support `Transfer-Encoding: chunked`.  When the
server shipped chunked responses by default (v0.17.0 / v0.17.1)
those clients reported "connection closed unexpectedly" immediately
after the first small response, because they were sizing their
receive buffer by the absent Content-Length header and treated the
TCP FIN as truncation.

### Flag

* **`--chunked`** — opt-in to `Transfer-Encoding: chunked`.  Flushes
  each JPP-stream message to the socket as it is produced; keeps the
  ~17× loopback TTFB win on large responses where the client can
  handle chunked transfer (browser demos, our C++ JpipClient).

* **`--no-chunked`** — accepted for backward compatibility; it is now
  the default, so the flag is a no-op.  Scripts that already pass it
  continue to work unchanged.

### No wire / library / test changes

`stream_jpp_response`, `StreamingJppParser`, the `?chunked`
detection in `JpipClient::fetch` / `fetch_streaming`, and the
WASM `jpip_feed_stream_*` entry points are all unchanged — the
server just no longer advertises chunked unless the operator asks
for it.  616/616 ctests and the browser demos continue to pass in
both modes.


# [0.17.1] - 2026-04-21

## JPIP gigapixel viewer — render-target cap + layout polish

Patch release refining the v0.17.0 browser demos based on real-
display testing.  No wire-format, library, or server changes.

### Gigapixel viewer (`subprojects/jpip_viewer.html`)

* **`?maxSize=WxH`** (default `1920x1080`).  Caps the WebGL render
  target and server-side precinct fetch so decode cost on 4K /
  ultrawide displays doesn't scale with the window.  The GPU
  upsamples the capped texture via `GL_LINEAR`.  Pass
  `?maxSize=window` to disable the cap and render at full window
  resolution.

* **`?fit=stretch|contain`** (default `stretch`).  Companion knob for
  `maxSize`: `stretch` CSS-scales the capped render target up to fill
  the window (today's behaviour), `contain` shows the canvas at
  native pixel scale centered in the window — matching how the
  foveation demo frames its fixed-size output.  No scaling
  artefacts at the cost of unused screen real estate around the
  canvas on displays larger than the cap.

* **Letterbox styling in `fit=contain`**.  A diagonal dark-stripe
  pattern replaces the default near-black body background in
  `fit=contain` mode so the margins around the centered canvas are
  visible on a dark UI theme.  The canvas gains a thin accent-blue
  outline + soft drop shadow so its edges are unambiguous.

* **Window-resize handler** (100 ms debounce).  Drag-resizing the
  browser window now re-centers the canvas, resets the GL viewport,
  clamps pan, and refetches — before this, the canvas was sized once
  at `connect()` and became stale on resize.  Pure CSS-only resizes
  (render target unchanged) skip the refetch.

### Demo cache-model help tables

Both `jpip_demo.html` and `jpip_viewer.html` documented the precinct
data-bin prefix as `Hp` (a pre-v0.16.1 misreading of the spec).  Per
§C.9.3.1 it is `P`; the server + library have emitted / accepted `P`
since v0.16.1.  The HTML help tables now match.  The `?fit=` help
row also gains a line break so `stretch` and `contain` don't run
together visually.

### Chunked-streaming bug fixes in `JpipClient` (from v0.17.0)

The v0.17.0 tag shipped with two portability issues that broke CI on
every non-macOS runner:

* **libstdc++ needs an explicit `#include <cstring>`** for `std::memchr`;
  libc++ pulls it in transitively.
* **MSVC's `<windows.h>`** defines a `min` macro that mangles
  `std::min(a, b)` at two call sites.  Wrapping as `(std::min)(a, b)`
  suppresses the macro expansion.

Both fixes landed in the v0.17.0 tag commit (`e70e432`) but the
release-notes text only called out the chunked-streaming work; noting
them here for bisect purposes.


# [0.17.0] - 2026-04-21

## JPIP — progressive HTTP-chunked delivery end-to-end (#297)

Stateless JPIP server + every in-repo client now pipeline JPP-stream
responses on the wire and through the parser, so large view-window
responses start landing in the decoder before the server has finished
building them.  Loopback time-to-first-byte for a 24 MB full-canvas
response drops from **7.4 ms to 0.44 ms** (17×); the HTTP/1.1 bodies
remain byte-identical between the chunked and Content-Length paths.

### Server (`source/apps/jpip_server/`)

* **HTTP/1.1 `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` by default.**  Each JPP
  message emitted by `stream_jpp_response` (new callback-driven
  primitive) is flushed to the socket as its own HTTP chunk.  The
  §C.6.1 `len=` rollback still works — it happens inside a reusable
  scratch buffer before each chunk is committed to the wire.
  `--no-chunked` opts out for clients that can't parse chunked.
  `build_jpp_stream` is preserved as a thin wrapper so benchmarks /
  tests that want a single buffered response are unchanged.

* **HTTP/1.1 `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` parsers** (`parse_http_chunked`,
  `decode_chunked_body`) plus the chunked response writers
  (`format_jpp_response_headers_chunked`, `format_chunk_header`,
  `format_last_chunk`) are exposed from `jpip_response.hpp`.

* **HTTP/3 path stays buffered** for now — progressive DATA-frame
  delivery would need an nghttp3 data-reader refactor; status quo is
  documented inline, QUIC connections behave identically to v0.16.1.

### Library (`source/core/jpip/`)

* **`StreamingJppParser`** (new, in `jpp_parser.hpp`).  Resumable JPP
  parser that carries `MessageHeaderContext` across `feed()` calls and
  buffers the tail bytes of an incomplete message until the next
  chunk supplies the rest.  `parse_jpp_stream` refactored to share a
  `try_decode_one_message` helper with the streaming parser so the two
  paths can't drift — every existing `parse_jpp_stream` caller
  behaves identically.

* **`JpipClient::fetch_streaming(..., on_progress)`**.  Drives an
  incremental chunked-transfer state machine straight into the new
  streaming parser, so `*out` grows as each HTTP chunk lands.
  `JpipClient::fetch(...)` now delegates to it — existing callers get
  streaming for free.

* `TcpStream::recv_some` and `TcpStream::recv_to_eof` added to support
  non-blocking drains from the chunked client path.

### WASM bindings (`subprojects/src/jpip_wrapper.cpp`)

* New exports `jpip_feed_stream_begin / _feed_stream / _feed_stream_end`
  alongside the existing `jpip_add_response` (preserved for one-shot
  callers).  A per-context `StreamingJppParser` + persistent
  `stream_tmp` `DataBinSet` keep the cache-model bookkeeping
  identical to `jpip_add_response` while tolerating chunk boundaries
  anywhere inside the stream.

### Browser demos (`subprojects/jpip_{demo,viewer}.html`)

* Swap `fetch().arrayBuffer()` for `response.body.getReader()` plus a
  `_jpip_feed_stream` loop, so the WASM parser starts consuming bytes
  as each chunk arrives.

* Auto-prefix `http://` on bare `host:port` server inputs (fixes the
  cryptic "URL scheme 'localhost' is not supported" `fetch()` error
  surfaced while testing on a real browser).

### Tests

* **`jpip_streaming_parser_{p0_04,ht_01}`** (new).  For every
  two-chunk split offset on a real JPP-stream, plus byte-at-a-time
  feeding and a `reset()`-based reuse pass, the streaming parser
  reconstructs an identical `DataBinSet` to the one-shot parser.
  This is the regression guard that the browser + C++ clients
  actually rely on.

* **`jpip_chunked_roundtrip`** (new).  Hand-rolled chunked HTTP
  responder drives `JpipClient::fetch_streaming` with a progress
  callback; asserts progress fires and sees bins grow monotonically.

* **`jpip_http_check`** extended to cover the chunked formatter,
  `decode_chunked_body` round-trips, and malformed-input rejection.

* **Node integration** (`tools/jpip_wasm_feed_test.mjs`).  Drives chunk
  sizes {1, 7, 100, 1024, full} against a live server, asserts
  `_jpip_feed_stream` state is byte-identical to `_jpip_add_response`
  state (canvas dims, precinct total, cache-model string).

* **Live browser**: both demos verified against the chunked server
  (`jpip_demo.html` on the 1920 foveation asset, `jpip_viewer.html`
  on the 21600 gigapixel asset).


# [0.16.1] - 2026-04-21

## JPIP server — interop-level spec fixes

Nine corrections to the stateless JPIP server in
`source/apps/jpip_server/` so that it reaches a level of spec
compliance at which mainstream interactive JPIP clients can
establish a session, cache received data, and drive a view-window
sequence through to a decoded image.  All fixes are grounded in
ISO/IEC 15444-9:2023 clauses; none are workarounds.

### Request handling

* **`len=` (§C.6.1) honoured.**  The client's "Maximum Response
  Length" field was previously parsed but ignored; the server
  would always emit the complete view-window response regardless
  of the cap.  `build_jpp_stream` now rolls back whole messages
  that would push the stream past `len`, and the terminating EOR
  switches to reason=4 (`ByteLimit`) instead of reason=2
  (`WindowDone`).  Clients that probe with small `len` values
  before committing to a large transfer now get a correctly-sized
  first response.

* **POST accepted (§C.1).**  HTTP POST was previously rejected
  with `405 Method Not Allowed`.  Interactive clients fall back
  to POST when the query would exceed the GET URL-length limit —
  for example when the cache-model field has grown to include
  hundreds of `P<n>` precinct identifiers.  The server now reads
  `Content-Length` (subject to a 16 MB cap), concatenates any
  body bytes that arrived alongside the headers, drains the rest
  from the socket, and hands the body to `parse_jpip_query` as
  the effective query string.

* **New request fields.**  `cnew`, `cid` (§C.3.3) and `len`,
  `quality` (§C.6.1) are now parsed into the `JpipRequest`
  struct; unknown fields remain silently ignored per §C.1.

* **`JPIP-cnew` session header (§C.3.3, §D.2.5).**  When the
  request carries `cnew=http`, the response now includes a
  `JPIP-cnew: cid=C<n>,path=jpip,transport=http` header.  The
  server is stateless — the `cid` is opaque to it and all cache
  state still flows through the client's `model=` field — but
  interactive clients will not commit received precincts to
  their session cache until this header arrives on the
  channel-establishment response, and without it they fall into
  a silent retry loop.

* **`target_id` basename.**  The `JPIP-tid` response header
  previously echoed the full server-side filesystem path.  Some
  clients then echo the TID back verbatim in `&tid=` on every
  follow-up request, producing unusually long, slash-laden query
  strings.  Strip to the basename so the TID is a short,
  path-free identifier per §D.4's "opaque string" wording.

### JPP-stream emission

* **Metadata-bin 0 emitted first (§A.3.6.1).**  The spec states
  that "servers should send metadata-bin 0 in advance of all
  other bins", and interactive clients use its arrival (even as
  an empty bin with `is_last=1`) as their session-binding
  signal.  Previously we emitted it third, after main-header and
  tile-headers; now it is the first message of every response.

* **Precinct chunking at 987 bytes per message.**  Whole
  multi-kB precinct payloads used to ship as a single Annex A
  message with `is_last=1`.  Clients that allocate a fixed ~1 KB
  cache-segment buffer and expect each message to fit alongside
  the encoded header fail to bookkeep larger messages.  The
  data-bin emitter now splits long payloads into 987-byte
  contributions with monotonically increasing `msg_offset`; only
  the final message carries `is_last=1`.  Data-bins smaller than
  one chunk still emit as a single message, so nothing changes
  for main-header, tile-header, or small precincts.

* **Ascending in-class-id precinct order.**  `resolve_view_window`
  returns keys in `(t, c, r, p_rc)` order.  Under the spec's
  `I = t + (c + s·C)·T` formula this produces component-major
  in-class-ids — 0, 3, 6, 9, … before 1, 4, 7, … — which clients
  that iterate their cache by ascending bin-id read as a gap
  they never fill.  They then refuse to advertise received
  precincts in their outgoing cache model because, from their
  perspective, the bins have not been "accepted" into the
  contiguous portion of the cache.  `build_jpp_stream` now
  sorts keys by `I` before emission so deliveries are gap-free.

* **Tile-header scoped to the view-window (§A.3.3).**  The spec
  requires the server to deliver the tile-header data-bin "for
  every tile whose identifier is found in the result of the
  view-window request".  Previously the server iterated every
  tile in the image, which on multi-tile codestreams (tens of
  thousands of tiles) crowded out precinct payload with empty
  tile-headers.  `build_jpp_stream` now derives the set of
  relevant tiles from `resolve_view_window`'s keys.

### Cache-model wire format

* **Precinct prefix corrected to `P` (§C.9.3.1).**  The server
  read `Hp<n>` as the precinct cache-descriptor prefix, which no
  spec-conformant client emits.  Clients use `P<n>`.  The
  consequence of the mismatch was severe: every precinct the
  client had already cached was silently dropped by our parser,
  so the server resent it.  On a stateful session this filled
  the client's cache with duplicates and wasted the bulk of the
  response budget on data the client would discard.  The parser
  now recognises both `P<n>` (spec form, accepted and emitted)
  and the legacy `Hp<n>` form (accepted for forward/backward
  compatibility).  `CacheModel::format` emits the canonical `P`
  form so our own client-side cache advertisements are
  spec-correct too.

### Known-good interop status

* Our own decoder round-trips the server's JPP-stream responses
  to pixel-identical output (verified against `u01_Books_4K_12bit_fov.j2c`).
* All 615 ctests pass.
* Interactive JPIP clients built in debug configuration decode
  and display imagery sourced from this server.
* Interactive clients built with aggressive release-mode
  optimisation remain subject to client-side undefined-behaviour
  issues in their cache-segment bookkeeping code (reproducible
  with any spec-conforming server including our own, and
  documented by their own UBSan build); no server-side workaround
  is possible.

# [0.16.0] - 2026-04-20

## JPIP wire format — EOR encoding corrected to match §D.3

The End-of-Response (EOR) message in our JPIP implementation was
being emitted and parsed as a fictional "message class 7" of the
Annex A header grammar.  Per ISO/IEC 15444-9:2023 §D.3, EOR is
**explicitly not an Annex A message** and uses a dedicated wire
format that starts with a special 0x00 identifier byte:

```
  0x00 | reason (1 byte) | body-length (VBAS) | body
```

Table A.2 lists only classes {0, 1, 2, 4, 5, 6, 8} — class 7 does
not exist.  Our code carried a `kMsgClassEOR = 7` constant that
dated back to an early draft.  On the wire this produced a
multi-byte Annex A message header with class-VBAS = 7, which a
conformant parser would either reject (Table A.1's `bb=00` EOR
sentinel trips first) or misinterpret as a new data-bin.

This release corrects both directions:

* **Emit** (`emit_eor` in `source/core/jpip/data_bin_emitter.cpp`)
  now writes exactly three bytes: `{0x00, reason, 0x00}`.  No
  MessageHeaderContext update is performed because EOR does not
  participate in Annex A's dependent-form class inheritance.

* **Parse** (`parse_jpp_stream` in
  `source/core/jpip/jpp_parser.cpp`) detects the 0x00 sentinel
  before attempting Annex A header decoding.  Bin-ID first-byte
  `bb=00` is already prohibited by Table A.1, so there is no
  ambiguity between an EOR terminator and a legitimate data-bin
  message.  The parser reads the reason byte, decodes the
  body-length VBAS, skips the (optional) body, and records the
  reason in the `DataBinSet`.

* Secondary bug fixed in the `EorReason` enum in
  `source/core/jpip/jpp_message.hpp`: Table D.2 reason codes
  **4 = Byte limit reached** and **5 = Quality limit reached**
  were swapped in our declaration.  Corrected, and added the
  previously-missing codes **6 = Session limit reached** and
  **7 = Response limit reached**.

* `kMsgClassEOR` is removed.  `msg_class_has_aux()` simplifies
  accordingly (the EOR exclusion is gone because EOR is no
  longer treated as a class).

### Regression coverage

New tests in `source/apps/jpip_parser_check/main.cpp`:

* Byte-exact assertion that `emit_eor(WindowDone)` produces
  `{0x00, 0x02, 0x00}`.
* Round-trip: parsing the emitted 3 bytes sets
  `DataBinSet::has_eor()` and yields `eor_reason() == 2`.
* Acceptance of an EOR with a non-empty body (skipped to the
  right offset, reason captured).
* Rejection of a truncated EOR (missing body-length VBAS) and of
  an EOR whose body-length exceeds the remaining bytes.

Full conformance suite: 615/615 pass on Linux + macOS + WASM +
Windows MSVC.

### Caller impact

`openhtj2k_jpip_server`, `openhtj2k_jpip_demo`, and the WASM
wrapper all call `emit_eor` and `DataBinSet::has_eor` /
`eor_reason` — none of them introspect the wire bytes, so no
caller changes were needed.  Binary compatibility: the symbol
`kMsgClassEOR` is removed; any out-of-tree code that referenced
it (unlikely — EOR is an internal protocol detail) must remove
the reference.  The `emit_eor` signature is unchanged.

This is a wire-format behaviour change for both our server's
output and our client's input, which is why this is v0.16.0 and
not v0.15.3.

# [0.15.2] - 2026-04-20

## Security — companion hang on the v0.15.1 security fixture (Windows MSVC only)

The same 231-byte fixture that exercised the v0.15.1 HT-block stack
overflow also reached a second pathological code path: in
`j2k_codeblock::create_compressed_buffer`
(`source/core/coding/coding_units.cpp`), the sum of attacker-
controlled `block->pass_length[i]` values (`layer_length`) was
clamped to the bytes remaining in `tile_buf` only on the
**first-layer** branch.  On any subsequent layer's append path, an
un-clamped `layer_length` flowed into `buf_chain::copy_N_bytes`,
whose `assert((pos + N) <= current_length)` precondition can be
violated by a malformed stream.

Platform asymmetry that hid this under v0.15.1:

* **Linux / macOS release builds** compile with `-DNDEBUG`
  (`CMakeLists.txt:141`), so `assert()` is a no-op.  The `memcpy`
  in `copy_N_bytes` silently over-reads the `tile_buf` node;
  HT-block decoding then rejects the resulting garbage with the
  existing "cleanup pass suffix length … is invalid" and v0.15.1
  "too many HT coding-pass segments" warnings and the process
  exits cleanly in < 5 ms.
* **Windows MSVC release builds** do not define `NDEBUG`
  (`CMakeLists.txt:148` sets only `/Ox`), so `assert()` is live.
  The assertion fires and the CRT invokes `abort()`, which on
  GitHub Actions Windows runners surfaces as a Windows Error
  Reporting dialog that waits for user input — producing the
  "60 s CTest timeout with zero output" symptom on both
  `windows-latest` (x86-64) and `windows-11-arm`.

Fix: hoist the `layer_length > tile_buf->get_remaining_bytes()`
clamp to the top of `create_compressed_buffer`, so it applies to
both the first-layer zero-copy path and the subsequent-layer
owned-buffer append path.  A `WARNING` printf matching the
v0.15.1 wording pattern is emitted so the malformed-input
rejection is observable in logs.  Platform-agnostic; no `#ifdef`
involved.

With the fix, the v0.15.1 regression fixture
(`tests/data/security_ht_segments_overflow.j2k`) completes in
~4 ms on Windows — the three downstream HT-block warnings fire,
exit code is 0, and the previously-skipped
`security_ht_segments_overflow` CTest case (un-skipped in
`tests/security_regressions.cmake`) passes on Windows alongside
Linux and macOS.  Full conformance suite remains green.

## API / library hygiene — remove `exit()` from the shared library

Five `exit(EXIT_FAILURE)` sites in the public decoder / encoder
API were terminating the host process from inside
`libopenhtj2k` on error paths.  A shared library should never
terminate for its embedder; long-running hosts (servers, daemons,
the WASM runtime, the JPIP demos) can't recover from a forced
process exit.

Replaced each site with `throw std::runtime_error(...)` carrying
a descriptive message.  The in-tree CLI wrappers
(`open_htj2k_dec`, `open_htj2k_enc`) already catch `std::exception`
around their decoder / encoder invocations; the two bare
constructor call sites in `source/apps/decoder/main_dec.cpp` (the
JPH colorspace probe and the line-based streaming path) are now
wrapped in the same try/catch so a missing input file produces a
single clean `ERROR: input file not found: <path>` line and
`EXIT_FAILURE`, not a `printf` + process abort.

Affected library sites:

* `source/core/interface/decoder.cpp` — file-path constructor's
  `std::filesystem::file_size()` / `stat()` failure branches.
* `source/core/interface/encoder.cpp` — unsupported input file
  extension rejection and two `read_pnmpgx` PPM/PGX header
  comment-read failure branches.

The library-side `printf("ERROR: …")` diagnostics that preceded
each `exit()` are dropped too — the exception carries the same
message, and catch blocks in the CLIs print it, so dual-reporting
is gone.

Regression test `api_decoder_throws_on_missing_file` in
`tests/security_regressions.cmake` runs `open_htj2k_dec` against
a nonexistent path and asserts a clean `"input file not found"`
message with no crash markers.  Total suite: 615 tests (+1 vs
v0.15.1), all green on Linux + macOS + WASM + (pending CI)
Windows.

No API header change — callers that were already expecting
exceptions from other error paths (missing main header, malformed
codestream, etc.) see no difference; callers that were relying on
`exit()` to terminate the process on a bad input file will now
get a catchable exception instead.

# [0.15.1] - 2026-04-20

## Security

### HT block decoding stack buffer overflow (all SIMD variants)

Fixes a reproducible stack buffer overflow in `htj2k_decode()`
reachable from a malformed JPEG 2000 / HTJ2K codestream.  A fixed
four-entry stack array `uint8_t all_segments[4]` was written by a
loop whose upper bound was `block->pass_length_count` (attacker-
controlled) rather than the array capacity.  Five or more non-zero
`pass_length[i]` entries wrote past the end and smashed the stack
canary on hardened release builds; ASan reported a 1-byte stack
buffer overflow on instrumented builds.  The same four variants
(generic, AVX2, NEON, WASM) also read `all_segments[0]`
uninitialised when `num_ht_passes > 0` but every `pass_length[i]`
was zero.

Impact: denial of service (crash) on every deployment exposed to
decoder input.  No remote code execution demonstrated; the written
byte is `static_cast<uint8_t>(i)`, not fully attacker-controlled.

Fix: bound `num_segments` to the array capacity (`return false`
when a sixth non-zero entry would overflow) and reject inputs
with zero non-zero entries.  Applied identically across all four
SIMD variants:

* `source/core/coding/ht_block_decoding.cpp` (generic)
* `source/core/coding/ht_block_decoding_avx2.cpp`
* `source/core/coding/ht_block_decoding_neon.cpp`
* `source/core/coding/ht_block_decoding_wasm.cpp`

Regression fixture `tests/data/security_ht_segments_overflow.j2k`
(231 bytes, SHA-256 `da756e7aa7421e1207b92b7651996ed4b328edb820bd30cdb5f4af953d1eb063`)
and a new `tests/security_regressions.cmake` with a CTest case
that asserts the patched guard fires and rejects any crash-marker
text in the output.  The suite now runs 614 tests.

Reported by:

* **IM JUN SEO** (KISIA, [@Jseanxx](https://github.com/Jseanxx))
* **OH HAN GUEL** (SANGMYUNG UNIVERSITY, [@5asever40-a11y](https://github.com/5asever40-a11y))

Both reporters provided a reproducer, full ASan + stack-canary
traces, root-cause analysis, and a correct suggested patch.

GitHub Security Advisory: GHSA-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx (CVE pending).

## Project

Added [`SECURITY.md`](SECURITY.md) documenting the private-report-to-
GitHub-advisory channel, report triage SLAs, the default fix-forward-
publicly disclosure posture, CVE coordination, credit practice, and
an in-scope / out-of-scope list.  Triggered by the report above.

# [0.15.0] - 2026-04-20

## JPIP — foveated streaming and gigapixel browsing (new)

Adds a complete client + server implementation of **JPIP**
(ISO/IEC 15444-9, 3rd edition): on-demand delivery of JPEG 2000
codestreams at the precinct level, over HTTP/1.1 or HTTP/3-over-QUIC.
Two interactive demos ship with it — mouse-driven **foveation**
(`open_htj2k_jpip_demo` + `jpip_demo.html`) and a pan-and-zoom
**gigapixel viewer** (`jpip_viewer.html`) for images larger than the
GPU texture limit — plus a foveation-vs-full-image `open_htj2k_jpip_benchmark`
CLI.  Both browser demos decode entirely in-page via WebAssembly; no
server-side decode, no plugin.

Try them at:
- **https://htj2k-demo.pages.dev/jpip_demo.html** — foveation
- **https://htj2k-demo.pages.dev/jpip_viewer.html** — gigapixel viewer

For architecture, wire format, and CLI usage, see the new
[**docs/jpip.md**](docs/jpip.md).

### Core library (`source/core/jpip/`)

Sixteen modules, ~6K lines of new C++:

* `precinct_index.{hpp,cpp}` — builds the `(t, c, r, p_rc) → s → I`
  lookup from a parsed main header, per §A.3.2.1.  `CodestreamIndex`
  carries per-(tile, component) precinct geometry, canvas geometry,
  tile-component extents, and precinct-partition parameters.
  `build_from_main_header_bin()` lets the client construct an index
  from just the header data-bin (no full codestream needed).
* `view_window.{hpp,cpp}` — §C.4 view-window resolver: maps
  `(fsiz, roff, rsiz)` to the set of precinct keys that contribute.
  Picks the discard level under round-direction "down" via
  `CodestreamIndex::max_NL`.  Full-image view-window (no `roff`/`rsiz`)
  gives the full precinct set.
* `vbas.{hpp,cpp}` — VBAS (variable-length big-endian) encode / decode
  per §A.2.1.  Used by every message header.
* `jpp_message.{hpp,cpp}` — JPP-stream message header codec: class +
  CSn + in-class id + msg-offset + msg-length + Aux (§A.2, Tables
  A.1 + A.2).  Classes 0 (precinct), 2 (tile header), 6 (main header),
  7 (EOR), 8 (metadata).
* `data_bin_emitter.{hpp,cpp}` — emits main-header / tile-header /
  metadata-bin-0 / precinct data-bin messages from a loaded codestream
  and a `CodestreamLayout`.
* `codestream_walker.{hpp,cpp}` — one-time pass over the source
  codestream to locate each tile-part and each tile-header marker
  segment (feeds the emitter).
* `packet_locator.{hpp,cpp}` — builds a per-precinct byte-range table
  by driving the decoder once with a packet observer.
* `jpp_parser.{hpp,cpp}` — consumes a JPP-stream byte buffer, appends
  every message body into a `DataBinSet` keyed by `(class, in_class_id)`.
  Strict in-order assumption for v1 (no gaps, no duplicates).
* `codestream_assembler.{hpp,cpp}` — two entry points:
  `reassemble_codestream` (server side, using the original codestream +
  `PacketLocator`) and `reassemble_codestream_client` (client side, no
  original bytes needed — patches the COD marker to LRCP, walks
  `(L, R, C, P)` with absent-packet 0x00 fill).
* `cache_model.{hpp,cpp}` — §C.9 client cache model with range
  compression (`Hm,Ht0-5,M0` instead of `Ht0,Ht1,Ht2,…`).  Parses
  `&model=` request fields; formats the outgoing advertisement.
* `jpip_request.{hpp,cpp}` — query parser (`fsiz`, `roff`, `rsiz`,
  `type=jpp-stream`, `model=...`).
* `jpip_response.{hpp,cpp}` — HTTP response framer with CORS headers
  and EOR message trailer.
* `jpip_client.{hpp,cpp}` — HTTP/1.1 client used by the native demo;
  accepts an optional `CacheModel` so successive fetches carry
  `&model=` without re-emitted headers.
* `tcp_socket.{hpp,cpp}` — cross-platform `TcpStream` /
  `TcpListener` (Winsock on Windows, BSD sockets elsewhere).
* `h3_server.{hpp,cpp}` / `h3_client.{hpp,cpp}` — HTTP/3 over QUIC
  via MsQuic + nghttp3.  `H3Client::fetch_multi` multiplexes N
  concurrent requests on one QUIC connection; the foveation demo
  uses it to send fovea + parafovea + periphery in a single RTT.

Progression-order policy: the client reassembler patches the COD
marker to LRCP so the `(L, R, C, P)` walk produces a well-formed
codestream regardless of the source's original ordering.  v1 supports
single-layer streams; multi-layer bins are re-emitted per layer
as-is.  SOP / EPH markers are refused by the reassembler.

### Native CLIs

* **`open_htj2k_jpip_server`** — stateless HTTP/1.1 (or HTTP/3 with
  `--h3 --cert ... --key ...`) server.  Loads one `.j2c`, builds the
  index + packet locator once.  Each request: `resolve_view_window`
  picks precinct keys, `build_jpp_stream` emits the complete
  JPP-stream (headers it knows the client lacks, plus precincts),
  sends with `Content-Type: application/jpp-stream`.  CORS preflight
  (`OPTIONS`) handled for cross-origin browser access.
* **`open_htj2k_jpip_demo`** — mouse-driven foveation over GLFW +
  OpenGL.  Three concentric cones (fovea / parafovea / periphery)
  follow the cursor; runs in-process (JPP round-trip), over HTTP/1.1
  (`--server host:port`), or over HTTP/3 (`--server-h3 host:port`).
  `--use-filter` bypasses the wire format via direct precinct
  filtering for A/B comparison.  `--window-size WxH` decouples the
  GPU texture size from the canvas; the Metal 16384-pixel cap is
  honoured so 21600 × 10800 NASA Blue Marble-class canvases run on
  Apple silicon.  `--reduce N` discards N DWT levels; foveation
  radii and ratios are CLI-tunable.
* **`open_htj2k_jpip_benchmark`** — sweeps an NxN gaze grid,
  reporting bandwidth reduction and decode speedup for foveated vs
  full-image delivery.  CSV export with `--csv`.

### Browser demos

* **`jpip_demo.html`** — mouse-over a canvas; three concurrent
  `fetch()` requests per gaze move return the three cones'
  JPP-streams, merged into a WASM-side `DataBinSet`, reassembled,
  decoded in WebAssembly, painted via WebGL2 (bilinear filtering).
  Multi-threaded SIMD WASM under cross-origin isolation; SIMD-only
  fallback otherwise.  Per-frame cache semantics: precincts reset
  each frame (periphery must decay when the gaze moves), headers
  preserved so the outgoing `&model=Hm,…,M0` stays truthful and the
  server stops re-sending tens of KB of headers.  Ratio controls
  (parafovea + periphery), reduce control, URL parameter support,
  URL-parameters + JPIP-query + cache-model reference tables inline.
* **`jpip_viewer.html`** — pan + zoom for images larger than the
  GPU texture cap.  Decoder's viewport-region path
  (`jpip_end_frame_region`) runs the IDWT only on the rows in the
  visible rectangle, with a column-limited horizontal 1D IDWT
  dropping samples outside the visible columns.  Pan events
  debounce + coalesce (trailing 60 ms window, in-flight latest-pending
  slot) so rapid trackpad input doesn't fan out into N fetches.

### Viewport-region decode (V2 — `jpip_end_frame_region`)

* `decoder.hpp`: new `set_row_limit(uint32_t)` and
  `set_col_range(uint32_t, uint32_t)` entries.  The line-based IDWT
  stops iterating after `row_limit`; rows before the viewport
  zero-skip for free via Phase 4's `adv_step` short-circuit; the
  horizontal 1D IDWT only processes columns in `[col_lo, col_hi)`.
* `subprojects/src/jpip_wrapper.cpp`: `jpip_end_frame_region(ctx,
  rgb, w, h, region_x, region_y, region_w, region_h)` clamps the
  region to the canvas at the active reduce level, precomputes an
  `xc` column LUT once per frame, and decodes only the in-viewport
  rows.  On a 42K × 10K canvas at `reduce=0`, a centred viewport
  decodes in ~400 ms in WASM where the full canvas took ~3000 ms.

### WASM C API (`subprojects/src/jpip_wrapper.cpp`)

New or changed entry points exported from the JPIP variant:

| Function | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `jpip_create_context(jpp, len)` | parse initial JPP-stream, build `CodestreamIndex` |
| `jpip_set_reduce(n)` | discard N DWT levels |
| `jpip_get_response_buffer(ctx, min_size)` | grow-only staging pointer; removes per-frame `_malloc` / `_free` |
| `jpip_add_response(ctx, buf, len)` | parse JPP-stream, merge into `DataBinSet`, update cache model |
| `jpip_get_cache_model(ctx)` | C-string for `&model=` advertisement (e.g. `Hm,Ht0,M0`) |
| `jpip_reset_cache(ctx)` | soft reset — drops precinct bins, keeps headers |
| `jpip_end_frame(ctx, rgb, w, h)` | full-canvas decode |
| `jpip_end_frame_region(ctx, rgb, w, h, x, y, rw, rh)` | viewport-region decode |
| `jpip_get_canvas_{width,height}` · `jpip_get_num_components` · `jpip_get_total_precincts` | asset metadata |

`UTF8ToString` added to `EXPORTED_RUNTIME_METHODS` for the
`jpip_get_cache_model` return value.

### Performance

* **Reassembler bucketing** — `reassemble_codestream_client` used to
  nest Layer × Resolution × Component × Precinct inside each tile,
  hash-probing the `DataBinSet` for every possible precinct ID.  Now
  does a single pass over delivered bins, buckets by tile-component
  pair, and emits touched (r, c) groups only.  On a 103K-precinct
  asset with ~500-bin viewports (heic2501a), the 10–50 ms dirty-frame
  cost drops to single milliseconds.
* **Server keys-driven emission** — `build_jpp_stream` now iterates
  the `keys` vector `resolve_view_window` already produces instead
  of hash-probing the full T × C × R × P grid.  Drops complexity
  from O(total_precincts) to O(|keys|); the foveation demo's 3×
  concurrent requests no longer amplify the full grid walk 3×.
* **Server: single `resolve_view_window` per request** — the HTTP/1.1
  and HTTP/3 paths used to call it a second time just for the log
  line.  Returns the count from `build_jpp_stream` instead.
* **WASM row callback** — `jpip_end_frame` and
  `jpip_end_frame_region` used to run a per-pixel 64-bit divide
  (`xc = xw · cw / ow`) and a captured-lambda `to_u8` call per
  channel.  Rewrite precomputes an `xc_lut[ow]` once per frame,
  hoists the bit-depth shift to a branchless `>> shift_pos`, marks
  the three row pointers and LUT `__restrict__`, and drops the
  lambda for inline branchless clamps.  The region variant clamps
  `rx1`/`ry1` to the canvas extent upfront so the per-pixel
  `xc >= cw` guard goes with it.
* **Persistent response buffer** — new `jpip_get_response_buffer`
  entry point exposes a grow-only staging pointer on the
  `JpipContext`.  Both demos now reuse it across every
  `add_response` instead of `_malloc` / write / `_free` cycling —
  3× per foveation frame eliminated.
* **Client cache-model advertisement** — both demos advertise
  `&model=Hm,Ht*,M0` so the server skips already-delivered headers
  (tens of KB per request).  Headers survive
  `jpip_reset_cache` as a soft reset; precincts do not.
* **Persistent decoder + single-tile reuse cache** — the viewer
  keeps one `openhtj2k_decoder` alive across frames with
  `enable_single_tile_reuse()`.  A `reduce_NL` change is not
  fingerprinted by the reuse cache, so the wrapper detects the
  transition and manually invalidates.
* **Debounced pan + in-flight coalescing** — viewer.  Trailing 60 ms
  window collapses rapid trackpad events into one fetch; a
  latest-pending slot guarantees the final viewport the user aimed
  at is the one rendered.
* **Viewer `lastFetchKey`** — drop `zoom × 1000` from the dedupe key
  since `computeReduce()` already collapses zoom jitter within the
  same reduce level.
* **Full-canvas region memset elimination** — skip the per-frame
  `O(ow · oh · 4)` zero-wipe in `jpip_end_frame_region` when the
  region fully covers the canvas (initial viewer load, fit-to-screen
  zoom).
* **Concurrent JPIP fetches (native + H3)** — the native demo's
  HTTP/1.1 path uses `std::async` on three `JpipClient::fetch`
  calls; the HTTP/3 path uses `H3Client::fetch_multi`.  Latency
  drops from sum(3 RTTs) to max(3 RTTs).

### Deployment

* `deploy/` — Dockerfile + Cloudflare Tunnel configuration for
  hosting the JPIP server.  Static-library link so the container has
  no `.so` dependency; `debian:bookworm-slim` base.
* `subprojects/index.html` — "JPIP Foveation" tab added to the demo
  navigation.
* CORS: `open_htj2k_jpip_server` emits `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`
  on both `OPTIONS` (preflight) and `GET` so the browser demos can
  fetch cross-origin.

### Fixes

* Export `CodestreamIndex` / `resolve_view_window` for MSVC DLL
  builds.
* `>8-bit` codestreams render correctly in the native demo
  (row-to-RGB uses `depth - 8` shift).
* WASM: refresh `HEAPU8` view after `_malloc` to handle ALLOW_MEMORY_GROWTH
  reallocation.
* WASM row duplication on `reduce > 0` (upsampling).
* WASM `?server=` URL parameter now fires before the module loads.
* WASM: use the full canvas resolution for the WebGL texture
  (bilinear filtering handles display downscale).
* `reassemble_codestream_client` reassembles from the persistent
  cache, not just the per-frame response, so headers from the
  initial handshake aren't lost.
* `header_cache` excludes precinct data-bins (foveation semantics).
* `invalidate_reuse` on `reduce_NL` change — prevents the single-tile
  reuse cache from returning a tile tree sized for the wrong
  resolution after a zoom.
* `jpip_demo.html`: reset cache per frame so the periphery decays
  when the gaze moves.
* `jpip_viewer.html`: invalidate single-tile reuse cache on
  `reduce_NL` change; handles JS-side zoom transitions cleanly.

### HTTP/3 transport fixes

* `QUIC_STREAM_START_FLAG_IMMEDIATE` on new streams — avoids a race
  where the peer sees the stream open before the header frame.
* Heap-allocate `QUIC_BUFFER` for async `StreamSend` — stack
  allocation would disappear before MsQuic read it.
* Compute QUIC stream IDs from type + arrival order instead of
  relying on MsQuic's `GetParam` (unreliable on macOS).
* H3 client fetches main-header on first connect; `--server-h3` mode
  guards against missing index before the first frame.

## Encoder

### TLM marker emission

`open_htj2k_enc` now emits a TLM (Tile-part Length Main) marker in
its output codestreams.  Downstream JPIP tools (packet locator,
precinct index) consume `TLM` to avoid a full codestream scan when
building the per-tile byte offset table.  Decoder surface exposes
tile-part lengths via the `TLM_marker` accessors.

### Fixes

* `PnmStreamReader`: PPM rasters whose first pixel byte is a
  whitespace character (0x20 / 0x0A / 0x0D / 0x09) were being
  consumed as header whitespace, shifting the stream by one byte.
  The reader now anchors on the single required delimiter after the
  `maxval` field and treats the next byte as raster regardless of
  value.
* `invoke` / `invoke_line_based_stream` encoder paths now surface
  exception messages from `std::exception::what()` instead of the
  generic `"encode failed"` string.

## Browser RTP demo polish (`rtp_demo.html`)

Incremental work on the video-replay demo shipped in 0.14.0.

### Sample hosting — Cloudflare R2 + edge caching

* Moved the default `.rtp` samples from the deploy bundle to a
  Cloudflare R2 bucket served through a custom domain with HTTP
  cache headers set by a small Pages Function.  Smaller deploys
  (the sample clips no longer ride along in every Pages build),
  faster cold starts (R2 objects hit the CDN edge).
* `.github/workflows/warm-rtp-cache.yml` — scheduled workflow that
  pre-warms the Cloudflare edge from a US runner so first-visit
  TTFB stays low after clip rotations.
* Preset dropdown: Sollevante 1080p/2160p (Netflix Open Content) as
  the new default, Spark part 6/8 and Chimera 4K as alternates.
  Legacy CloudFront URL still supported.

### Paced-mode frame dropping

* Opt-in UI checkbox + `?drop=1` URL parameter.  When enabled,
  paced mode skips frames whose RTP-clock target is already past —
  useful on slow hardware; off by default so marginal decoders play
  smoothly (slow-motion) rather than stuttering.
* `?drop_periods=N` (default 8 frame-periods ≈ 267 ms at 29.97 fps)
  controls the slack before dropping kicks in.
* `?preroll=N` (default 3) — frames decoded back-to-back before the
  paced wall clock anchors.  Absorbs cold-start decode spikes (SIMD
  warmup, WASM JIT).

### Paced display via `requestAnimationFrame`

* Display pacing moved from `setTimeout` to `requestAnimationFrame`
  so paint happens on the vsync boundary rather than chasing one.
* Network reads run on a background pump decoupled from the consumer
  rate, so a slow decoder can't stall the fetch pipeline.

### 2 GB heap cap + auto-reduce

* Raised `MAXIMUM_MEMORY` from 1 GB to 2 GB (Emscripten link flag)
  for 4K content.
* Auto-reduce starts at `reduce_NL=1` for 4K streams so typical
  displays get a smooth 2K decode without the user having to flip
  a knob.

## Build / packaging

### Shared library rename — `libopenhtj2k`

The installed shared library is now `libopenhtj2k.so.<major>` (plain
`libopenhtj2k` with no separator) instead of `libopen_htj2k`.  Matches
Debian's shlib policy for version-sonamed libraries so downstream
packaging is linear.  The CMake target name is unchanged; only the
output filename moves.

### Docker

* `deploy/Dockerfile` — `debian:bookworm-slim` base, static-linked
  server (no `.so` dependency), runs on a non-root user.

## Documentation

* [**docs/jpip.md**](docs/jpip.md) — complete reference for the JPIP
  subsystem: server + demo CLIs, browser demos, benchmark tool,
  core architecture, data-bin classes, JPIP sequence number /
  identifier derivation, viewport-region decode (V2), cache-model
  wire format (§C.9), WASM C API, deployment pointer, known
  limitations.

# [0.14.0] - 2026-04-14

## Browser-side HTJ2K video playback

Turns the existing still-image WASM build into a full browser video
player for RFC 9828 `.rtp` recordings, with multi-threaded WASM,
WebGL2 GPU rendering, Display-P3 on supported hardware, and
automated deployment to Cloudflare Pages.  The existing still-image
`index.html` demo is unchanged in behavior but gets the new layout
polish (tab navigation, iOS text-size fix).

### Multi-threaded WASM

* New targets `libopen_htj2k_mt.js` (scalar + pthreads) and
  `libopen_htj2k_mt_simd.js` (SIMD + pthreads) in
  `subprojects/CMakeLists.txt`.  Thread pool size defaults to
  `navigator.hardwareConcurrency || 4`.  Requires
  Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy + Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy headers
  (served by Cloudflare Pages via `_headers`; a service worker
  `coi-serviceworker.js` is shipped as a fallback for local / file://
  access).
* `subprojects/CMakeLists.txt` switched from `emmalloc` to `dlmalloc`
  for all four variants.  emmalloc had a small-allocation corruption
  bug that crashed `std::vector` destruction inside the RTP
  reassembly pipeline.
* `subprojects/src/wrapper.cpp` adds a new `create_decoder_mt(data,
  size, reduce_NL, num_threads)` entry point (passing `0` picks
  `navigator.hardwareConcurrency`) and a `get_hardware_concurrency()`
  helper.
* `subprojects/open_htj2k_dec.mjs` (Node CLI) gains a `-num_threads`
  / `-t` flag; with it set to anything but 1, prefers the multi-
  threaded builds.  Also fixes a regex ordering bug so the pthreads
  JS glue can be loaded inside `new Function()` (needed because the
  bottom of the generated module has an `await import(...)` for
  worker bootstrap that we don't need on the main thread).

### Browser RTP replay demo (`rtp_demo.html`)

* New page that fetches an RFC 9828 `.rtp` file (Spark fixture
  format — `[0xFFFF][length][RTP]...`) from a URL, local file, or
  preset dropdown; reassembles into JPEG 2000 codestreams via a
  WASM-side `RtpSession`; decodes each frame and paints to canvas.
* Ports `source/apps/rtp_recv/rfc9828_parser.cpp` and `frame_handler.cpp`
  into the WASM build as four per-flag-set OBJECT libraries
  (`rtp_reassembly_{,simd_,mt_,mt_simd_}objs`).  One per wrapper
  variant because mismatched `-msimd128` / `-pthread` flags produce
  different libc++ layouts and crash inside `std::deque::pop_front`
  destruction.
* New C API in `wrapper.cpp`: `rtp_session_create/destroy/reset`,
  `rtp_push_packet`, `rtp_peek_frame_size`, `rtp_pop_frame`,
  `rtp_pop_frame_{matrix,range,primaries,transfer,timestamp}`,
  and stats getters (`rtp_frames_emitted`, `rtp_frames_dropped`,
  `rtp_seq_gaps`, `rtp_packets_received`, `rtp_last_error`).
* Parser in `subprojects/rtp_parser.js`: async generator with a
  growable rolling buffer (amortised O(N)), try/finally cleanup
  that cancels the underlying `ReadableStream` on exit so
  `Blob.stream()` / `fetch` resources don't leak across
  play→stop→play cycles.
* Auto-selects BT.601 or BT.709 based on RFC 9828
  `MatrixCoefficients`; falls back to BT.709 for unknown values and
  honors a user-selectable override dropdown.
* Auto-reduce: a 4K input stream downshifts to `reduce_NL=1` after
  the first frame so typical displays get a smooth 2K decode.

### WebGL2 renderer

* Replaces the Canvas 2D `createImageData` + `putImageData` path
  with a WebGL2 renderer.  Two render programs compiled up front:
  * Packed path: takes `invoke_decoder_to_rgba` output as an RGBA8
    texture; fragment shader applies the YCbCr→RGB matrix on GPU
    (skips `apply_ycbcr_bt601/709_to_rgba` CPU pass).  Coefficients
    derived from the same `/16384` fixed-point values as the CPU
    path for bit-parity within ±1/255.
  * Planar path: three `R8` textures at native per-component sizes
    (Y at luma size, Cb/Cr at chroma size), shader samples three
    textures.  Cb/Cr use `LINEAR` filter → hardware bilinear chroma
    upsampling for free.  Upload bandwidth ~50% lower for 4:2:2 and
    ~75% lower for 4:2:0 compared to the packed path.  New WASM
    export `invoke_decoder_planar_u8(dec, y_buf, cb_buf, cr_buf)`
    with per-component signedness (the packed path uses
    `is_signed[0]` for all three — a latent bug for typical Y-
    unsigned + Cb/Cr-signed streams).
* Display-P3 colorspace: sets `gl.drawingBufferColorSpace =
  'display-p3'` when the OS+browser+display all support it;
  `Canvas2DRenderer` uses the matching `{ colorSpace: 'display-p3'
  }` option on `getContext` and `createImageData`.
* Context-loss handlers re-compile the programs and re-create the
  VAO + textures on `webglcontextrestored`.
* URL parameter `?renderer=auto|webgl|2d` + dropdown in the header
  for A/B testing.

### Video-player UI

* Full-width canvas with `aspect-ratio` set dynamically from the
  first frame's full-resolution dimensions — no scrollbars, no
  fixed height cap, letterboxes/pillarboxes when the canvas doesn't
  match the container.
* Stats move from a right-side table into a horizontal chip strip
  below the video.  Display FPS is the primary chip with accent
  color.  Show/Hide toggle above the strip.
* **Fullscreen** button (`⛶`), double-click-video, and keyboard
  shortcut all toggle native fullscreen on the canvas wrapper only
  (not the whole page).  Display FPS HUD appears in the top-right
  corner with a transparent background (text-shadow outline for
  readability), visible only while in fullscreen.
* **Click-to-pause** on the video (single click, with a 220 ms
  window to disambiguate from double-click fullscreen).
* **Spacebar** toggles pause/resume; suppressed when focus is in
  an `INPUT`/`SELECT`/`TEXTAREA`/contenteditable so URL typing
  still works.
* **Tab navigation** between `index.html` and `rtp_demo.html` via a
  two-tab bar below the site header; active tab highlighted with
  accent color.
* iOS text-size-adjust fix (`text-size-adjust: 100%`) so the
  progressive-resolution cells in `index.html` and the stats strip
  in `rtp_demo.html` don't inflate on iOS Safari / iOS Edge.

### Paced-mode pause compensation

* Previously, pausing for N seconds left paced mode's wall-clock
  target N seconds behind the RTP timeline, so on resume the
  decoder ran flat-out until the two timelines re-converged —
  visible as a multi-second fast-forward sprint.  `setPaused` now
  accumulates pause durations into a module-level `totalPausedMs`
  that is added to the paced target, making resume seamless.

### Performance

* Replaced `setTimeout(0)` event-loop yields with
  `MessageChannel.postMessage` (no 4 ms clamp under nesting), which
  was costing ~32 ms/frame on 1080p content — enough for ASAP
  playback to be visibly slower than paced playback under load.
* Diagnostic infrastructure opt-in behind `?verbose=1`:  once-per-
  second console log with input-bytes, parsed-bytes, decode-time,
  drops, pending-queue depth, display FPS; first-frame dump of
  per-component sizes, signedness, depth, and RFC 9828 metadata.

### Automated deployment (Cloudflare Pages)

* New GitHub Actions workflow
  `.github/workflows/deploy-wasm-demo.yml`:  runs on push to `main`
  or `feat/wasm-rtp-demo` (or manual dispatch), installs Emscripten
  via `mymindstorm/setup-emsdk@v14` with `actions-cache-folder:
  emsdk-cache`, builds all four variants, stages a deploy directory
  (HTML pages, JS glue, WASM, sample codestreams, `coi-serviceworker`,
  `_headers` file with COOP/COEP), and uploads to Cloudflare Pages
  via `cloudflare/pages-action@v1`.
* `conformance_data/` gains the four `.j2c` samples the still-image
  demo's preset dropdown referenced (`kodim23_mono`, `u04_small`,
  `u10_part1_lossless`, `u10_part15_lossless`) so the deployed
  site's dropdown works end-to-end.

Both encoder and decoder are unchanged at the native / Part 1 / HT
coding level — this release is a rendering / transport / deployment
milestone, not an algorithmic one.  All 582 conformance tests still
pass.

# [0.13.2] - 2026-04-13

## Performance — 4K @ 60 fps on Apple Silicon (RTP receiver)

* RTP receiver: close the 3.9 ms live-vs-offline decode gap on M3 Max,
  bringing the live receiver from ~50 fps to ~60 fps on 4K 4:2:2 HT
  at 1.7 bpp with `--threads 2`.  Two optimizations:

  1. **Codestream cache warmup** (`pipeline_multi_threaded.cpp`):
     after `init_borrow()`, a volatile read loop forces every cache
     line of the codestream into the decode core's L1/L2.  The
     recv_thread populates frame data on a different core, so without
     this sweep the HT decoder's scattered codeblock reads hit L3/SLC
     (~20 ns) instead of L2 (~5 ns).  Saves ~1.7 ms/frame compared
     to the unaided zero-copy path.

  2. **CRP-cached packet traversal** (`coding_units.cpp`):
     after the first frame's progression-order traversal, cache every
     (component, resolution, precinct) tuple in a flat vector.
     Subsequent frames replay this vector directly — the
     progression-order switch, the 4D `is_packet_read` vector
     allocation, and all per-frame `p_x`/`p_y`/`x_examin`/`y_examin`
     heap allocations are skipped entirely.  Saves ~1.4 ms/frame.

  Supporting change: `buf_chain::reset()` in `codestream.hpp` reuses
  the tile_buf across frames instead of heap-allocating per frame.

  Results on M3 Max (4K 4:2:2, 1.7 bpp, `--threads 2`):
    Before: avg 20.0 ms/frame, ~50 fps, many decode-slot evictions
    After:  avg 16.86 ms/frame, ~59-60 fps, 7 evictions (cold start)

  All 582 conformance tests pass.  No SIMD code touched — AVX2, NEON,
  and WASM paths are unaffected.

# [0.13.1] - 2026-04-12

## Build fixes

* RTP receiver: fix `-DOPENHTJ2K_RTP=ON` build on macOS.  The
  experimental `open_htj2k_rtp_recv` target unconditionally included
  `<GL/gl.h>` and `<GL/glext.h>` from `source/apps/rtp_recv/gl_loader.hpp`
  and `gl_renderer.cpp`.  Those paths exist on Linux but not under the
  Apple OpenGL framework, where the headers live at `<OpenGL/gl3.h>`
  and `<OpenGL/gl3ext.h>`, breaking the configure-and-build cycle on
  Apple Silicon and Intel Macs.  `gl_loader.hpp` now selects the
  Apple paths under `__APPLE__` (and defines `GL_SILENCE_DEPRECATION`
  to quiet Apple's legacy-OpenGL warnings) while keeping the Linux
  branch unchanged; the redundant `<GL/gl.h>` include in
  `gl_renderer.cpp` is dropped since the loader header already brings
  in the right GL headers for the platform.  Verified by a clean
  configure + build of the RTP target on macOS (Apple Silicon,
  AppleClang 21).  Linux builds are byte-identical because the
  non-Apple `#else` branch is the original two includes.

# [0.13.0] - 2026-04-12

## HDR display pipeline (RTP receiver)

* RTP receiver: complete HDR colour pipeline in the fragment shader.
  Extends the v0.12.0 shader path (which shipped the `GL_R16` plane
  upload and the BT.2020 YCbCr→RGB matrix) with inverse EOTF,
  linear-light gamut mapping, hard-clip tone mapping, and a display
  encoding stage, so a BT.2020 PQ or HLG broadcast source renders
  with the correct transfer and primaries on an SDR display.  New
  `source/apps/rtp_recv/color_pipeline.hpp` holds the stage-selection
  state (`ColorPipelineParams`) that flows from RFC 9828
  `TRANS` / `PRIMS` fields through `AssembledFrame → DecodedFrame`
  into the shader as uniforms.  The fragment shader runs: planar
  YCbCr → RGB matrix (existing) → inverse EOTF (gamma / PQ / HLG) →
  BT.2020→BT.709 gamut matrix in linear light → hard clip to
  display gamut → sRGB (or gamma-2.2, or linear) display encoding.
  Three new CLI flags drive the pipeline:
    * `--transfer {auto|gamma|pq|hlg}` — inverse EOTF choice;
      `auto` reads RFC 9828 `TRANS` (ITU-T H.273 TransferCharacteristics)
      and defaults to gamma if missing or unsupported.
    * `--display-primaries {bt709|bt2020}` — target gamut for the
      linear-light matrix stage; default `bt709`.
    * `--display-encoding {srgb|gamma22|linear}` — the output
      transfer curve written into the framebuffer; default `srgb`.
  Defaults (`--transfer auto --display-primaries bt709
  --display-encoding srgb`) reproduce the v0.12.0 shader path's
  appearance on SDR BT.709 sources modulo a bounded re-encoding
  drift (the gamma inverse followed by sRGB re-encoding is not a
  byte identity, but differs by at most 1 LSB in 8-bit quantised
  output).  `--color-path cpu` remains explicitly scoped out of the
  HDR pipeline and runs the legacy scalar YCbCr→RGB path.

## Decoder threading redesign (starting point of Option A)

Three-commit precursor series that reshapes the line-based streaming
decoder's driver to enable per-component IDWT dispatch to pool worker
threads.  Peak wall-time on 4K 4:2:2 12-bit HT moves from 12.14 ms
@ `--threads 2` (v0.12.0 sweet spot) to 10.46 ms @ `--threads 6` — a
14% improvement and the first time the decode ceiling has cleared
90 fps on this fixture.

* Decoder: nested `ThreadPool` dispatch precursor
  (`source/core/coding/subband_row_buf.cpp:203`).  Removes the
  `!is_worker_thread` bail that forced `decode_strip_core` onto the
  serial path whenever reached from inside a pool worker.
  Re-entrant dispatch is safe because `push_batch` / `try_run_one`
  never hold `tasks_mutex` across task invocation — the popped task
  is moved out of the ring under the lock and invoked unlocked, so a
  worker pushing its own subtasks and draining them via `spin_wait`
  + `try_run_one` cannot self-deadlock.  No-op for current callers
  on its own (the guard was only ever reached from main), but a
  precondition for the component-parallel IDWT dispatch that follows
  in this release.  Also adds a re-entrancy contract comment on
  `ThreadPool::try_run_one` documenting the lock discipline.
  Perf-neutral on threads={2,4,8}.
* Decoder: per-component strip scratch buffer infrastructure.  Adds
  `sprec_t *strip_buf; size_t strip_buf_floats` fields to
  `j2k_tcomp_line_dec` plus a public helper
  `j2k_tile_component::pull_strip_into_buf(count, stride_floats)`
  that grows the scratch on demand, pulls `count` rows via
  `pull_line_ref` + `memcpy`, and returns the base pointer.  32-byte
  aligned so AVX2 finalize kernels can read it with unaligned loads
  at full speed; persistent across frames under single-tile reuse
  (freed in `finalize_line_decode` on tile-component teardown).
  Unused by the driver in that commit — pure infrastructure — then
  consumed by the next commit.
* Decoder: component-parallel IDWT strip pulls in the line-based
  streaming driver.  Reshapes `j2k_tile::decode_line_based_stream`
  from a row-at-a-time `for y { for c pull_line_ref }` loop into a
  strip-granular driver.  The outer loop walks the tile in strips
  of `max(tcomp[0].codeblock_size.y, 64)` luma rows (rounded up to
  the max `SIZ.YRsiz` across components so chroma strip boundaries
  always land on an integer chroma row).  At the top of every strip
  each component's rows are pulled into its strip scratch via
  `pull_strip_into_buf`, and the pull phase dispatches `NC`
  per-component tasks through `ThreadPool::push_batch`.  The calling
  thread pitches in via `try_run_one` inside a local barrier
  helper (`dec_strip_barrier_wait` in `coding_units.cpp`).  The
  inner finalize + callback loop is unchanged byte-for-byte and
  reads `strip_ptrs[c] + row_in_strip * stride`.  One non-obvious
  correctness trap is preserved through the rewrite: the existing
  driver iterates over `ci[0].csize_y` and calls `pull_line_ref`
  unconditionally for `c=0..2` regardless of `SIZ.YRsiz`, because
  MCT demands 4:4:4 and the three components share geometry in
  component row space.  The strip-granular pull phase uses
  `count = strip_y1 - strip_y0` for MCT main, and the
  subsampling-aware `(strip_y1+yr_c-1)/yr_c - strip_y0/yr_c`
  formula for non-MCT and MCT extras `c>=3`.  A unified
  "divide by yr_c everywhere" formula breaks conformance fixture
  `p0_10` (which declares `YRsiz=4` on all three MCT components).
  The minimum strip height of 64 luma rows amortises the per-strip
  pull dispatch + barrier: broadcast HTJ2K fixtures use `cb_h`
  values as small as 8 to shorten sub-codestream latency, and
  dispatching `NC` tasks every 8 luma rows spends more time in
  mutex + barrier than in IDWT.

  Measured on the Spark 4K 4:2:2 12-bit HT fixture (200 frames × 3
  loops via `rtp_decode_profile`, reuse path, Ryzen 9 9950X):

  | `--threads` | v0.12.0 | v0.13.0 | delta    | ceiling fps |
  |-------------|--------:|--------:|---------:|------------:|
  | 2           | 12.14 ms| 12.60 ms|   +0.46  |       79.4  |
  | 3           |     --  | 11.12 ms|          |       89.4  |
  | 4           | 12.41 ms| 10.70 ms|   −1.71  |       92.9  |
  | **6**       |     --  |**10.46 ms**|        |     **94.9**|
  | 8           | 13.78 ms| 11.41 ms|   −2.37  |       87.1  |

  `threads=2` has a small (~0.4 ms) regression because with only
  `main + 2 workers` the per-component pulls cannot add a fourth
  compute stream and the strip scratch memcpy is not absorbed.
  This is the trade-off for the ~15% peak improvement at
  `threads=4..6`, and motivates the default-threads bump below.
* `open_htj2k_rtp_recv`: bump `--threads` default from 2 to 4.  The
  v0.12.0 default was benchmarked at the pre-A1b sweet spot; the
  component-parallel IDWT dispatch moves the new sweet spot to
  `threads=4..6` on 4K 4:2:2 broadcast HT.

All 582 conformance tests pass, including `p0_10` (`YRsiz=4` MCT)
and `dec_lossless` / `comp_lossless_odd` under `ctest -j`.

# [0.12.0] - 2026-04-11

## HDR groundwork (experimental)
* RTP receiver: for sources with a luma bit depth greater than 8,
  the shader color path now uploads planes as `GL_R16` instead of
  right-shifting to `GL_R8` at the CPU -> GPU boundary, preserving
  the full source bit depth end-to-end.  A new CPU-side helper
  (`clamp_i32_plane_to_u16` in `planar_shift.hpp`) performs the
  int32 -> uint16 clamp with an AVX2 inner loop (8 samples per
  iteration).  The fragment shader renormalizes via a new
  `uNormScale` uniform (`65535 / ((1 << depth) - 1)`) so the
  existing BT.601 / BT.709 matrix math runs in the source's native
  `[0, 1]` range regardless of input depth.  8-bit sources keep the
  unchanged `GL_R8` path; `uNormScale = (1, 1, 1)` for those, which
  is an IEEE 754 identity multiply, so the 8-bit output is
  bit-identical to 0.11.1.  `GL_R16` is normalized (not
  `GL_R16UI`) so `GL_LINEAR` filtering still works for 4:2:2 / 4:2:0
  chroma upsampling.  A 12-bit 4K 4:2:2 live soak runs at
  source-locked cadence with zero decode-slot evictions and no GL
  errors.  Note that this is a texture-format and pipeline change
  only; no PQ / HLG transfer-function decoding and no gamut mapping
  are implemented, so a BT.2020 PQ source will preserve its LSBs
  but still render with the display's native gamma curve.
* RTP receiver: routes RFC 9828 frames carrying `MAT = 9`
  (ITU-T H.273 BT.2020 NCL) through the correct YCbCr -> RGB matrix
  instead of erroring out with an unsupported-MAT log.  New
  `YCBCR_BT2020_FULL` and `YCBCR_BT2020_NARROW` constants, derived
  from `Kr = 0.2627`, `Kg = 0.6780`, `Kb = 0.0593` per ITU-R
  BT.2020 Table 4.  `select_coefficients_from_mat()` gains a case
  for `MAT = 9`; `MAT = 10` (BT.2020 CL / constant-luminance), 11
  (SMPTE ST 2085), and 12-14 (chroma-derived / ICtCp) are
  intentionally not mapped.  The `--colorspace bt2020` CLI value
  is accepted as the `S = 0` fallback and composes with `--range
  full` / `--range narrow` the same way `bt601` and `bt709` do.
  As with the `GL_R16` work above, this is a matrix change only;
  a BT.2020 HDR source still needs PQ / HLG decoding and gamut
  mapping to render correctly on an SDR display.

## Tests
* Fix intermittent `ctest -j` failure on the encoder round-trip
  tests.  `comp_lossless` / `comp_lossless_odd` were flaky under
  parallel ctest execution (`imgcmp` error "File
  kodim23lossless.ppm is not found"), while serial ctest always
  passed.  Root cause was a race between the `cleanup_artifacts`
  fixture (which `file(REMOVE *.ppm *.pgm *.pgx)` in the build
  directory) and the encoder round-trip chain.  The decoder
  conformance tests declared `FIXTURES_REQUIRED test_artifacts`
  but the encoder tests did not, so ctest was free to schedule
  `cleanup_artifacts` concurrently with `enc_lossless ->
  dec_lossless -> comp_lossless`, wiping the intermediate `.ppm`
  between `dec_lossless` writing it and `comp_lossless` reading
  it.  Fix: declare `FIXTURES_REQUIRED test_artifacts` on all nine
  encoder tests.  Five consecutive `ctest -j32` runs now pass
  582 / 582.

## Documentation
* README restructured from 318 lines into a concise ~165-line
  overview (elevator pitch, highlights, quick build, CLI
  quick-start with three examples and the key flags per app,
  supported formats, docs index) plus a new `docs/` directory
  with one file per topic:
  `docs/building.md` (full CMake flag reference, native build,
  WebAssembly build + Node.js CLI, RTP receiver prerequisites),
  `docs/cli_encoder.md` (full `open_htj2k_enc` option reference),
  `docs/cli_decoder.md` (full `open_htj2k_dec` option reference),
  and `docs/cli_rtp_recv.md` (full `open_htj2k_rtp_recv` option
  reference, kernel `rmem_max` tuning, 4K @ 60 fps hardware
  requirements, known issues including the NVIDIA + Mutter +
  Wayland + vsync interaction).  Runtime `-h` remains the primary
  reference; `docs/` is for offline browsing.
* Corrected the README's CLI I/O table notes.  Previously the
  table claimed "PPM supports subsampled (4:2:2, 4:2:0)
  components", which is wrong because PPM is packed RGB; what
  actually happens is a nearest-neighbour chroma upsample on the
  decoder side when `-ycbcr bt601|bt709` is set.  The "streaming
  path accepts subsampled PGX" note was misleading because both
  the batch and streaming encoder paths support multi-file PGX
  input.  The TIFF row said "8/16 bpp" which reads as bits per
  pixel (an 8-bit RGB TIFF is 24 bpp); it should read "8 or 16
  bits per sample" and also state that TIFF input is batch-only.
  The RAW row had no note at all.  PGM and PPM are now separate
  rows since they carry different notes.
* `docs/cli_rtp_recv.md`: `--colorspace` documents the new `bt2020`
  value and calls out the current scope limitation (matrix only;
  no PQ / HLG EOTF, no gamut mapping yet).

# [0.11.1] - 2026-04-11

## Documentation
* README: update the RTP receiver capability claim from
  "sustains 4K @ 30 fps" to "sustains 4K @ 60 fps on modern x86-64
  with --threads 2", to reflect the v4-perf work that shipped in
  0.11.0. Retitles the "Hardware requirements" section to
  "4K @ 60 fps sustained", rewrites the CPU / headless / network /
  display bullets around the new ceiling, and points at the
  offline profiler at
  `source/apps/rtp_recv/tools/rtp_decode_profile.cpp` as the
  reproduction harness. Network bullet bumped from ~50 MB/s to
  ~100 MB/s for broadcast 4K 4:2:2 HT at ~1.7 bpp at 60 fps.
  Explicitly notes that `--color-path cpu` has a lower ceiling
  than the shader path because it runs the full YCbCr->RGB matrix
  on the CPU (a different hot path than the phase-1-optimised
  planar shift the shader path uses). Display guidance: at
  60 fps source + 60 Hz display the RTP-timestamp pacer naturally
  lands one present per vblank under `--no-vsync`; `--pace-fps`
  only matters for mismatched rates. No code change.

# [0.11.0] - 2026-04-11

## Performance
* RTP receiver: AVX2 fast path for the planar `int32 -> u8` shift
  callback used by the shader color path. Processes 8 samples per
  iteration with a clamp + arithmetic-shift-right + `packus_epi32`
  + `packus_epi16` chain; cuts the scalar shift-to-u8 cost on 4K 4:2:2
  broadcast HT from ~4.56 ms/frame to ~1.70 ms/frame. Scalar tail
  covers `width % 8`. Byte-equal against the scalar reference across
  every `(shift, width)` residue in `--smoke-test`.
* Decoder: persistent single-tile cache for streaming reuse. New
  opt-in public API (`openhtj2k_decoder::enable_single_tile_reuse` +
  `invoke_line_based_stream_reuse`) lets the same decoder instance
  skip `create_resolutions`, the `j2c_packet[]` allocation, the
  ~50-call `aligned_alloc` storm inside `init_line_decode`, and the
  matching frees inside `finalize_line_decode` on every frame after
  the first. The POC iteration and per-frame `read_packet` still run
  against cached codeblock state via new helpers
  (`j2k_tile::prepare_for_next_frame`,
  `j2k_codeblock::reset_for_next_frame`,
  `j2k_precinct_subband::reset_for_next_frame`,
  `tagtree_node::reset_for_next_frame`, `idwt_2d_state_rewind`).
  An FNV-1a fingerprint over the SIZ/COD/QCD scalars and COC/QCC/RGN
  counts guards the cache: any main-header shape change invalidates
  automatically and falls back to the legacy path. Default off; the
  legacy path is byte-for-byte untouched. Saves ~3 ms/frame on 4K
  4:2:2 broadcast HT when enabled.
* Decoder: per-strip codeblock enumeration cache in
  `j2k_subband_row_buf::trigger_prefetch`. The first call per
  (subband, strip) walks the precinct / codeblock tree via
  `access_precinct` / `access_pband` and captures every block's
  position, size, and strip-relative offset into a persistent
  `strip_cache_` on the row-buf object. Every subsequent call —
  i.e. every frame after the first under single-tile reuse —
  iterates the cached list and skips the tree walk entirely.
  Block empty-vs-nonempty status is NOT cached because
  `j2k_codeblock::reset_for_next_frame()` clears `num_passes` at
  frame boundaries; the hot path branches on `num_passes` per
  block, which is cheap relative to the tree walk it replaces.
  Cache invalidation is implicit: any main-header shape change
  destroys the tile and its row-buf objects, which drops the cache.
  Saves another ~4 ms/frame on 4K 4:2:2 broadcast HT (17.07 ms ->
  13.13 ms live decode time). Byte-equal against the legacy path
  across the full 582-test conformance suite plus a 50-frame
  Y/Cb/Cr plane dump.
* Combined receiver ceiling on 4K 4:2:2 1.7-bpp broadcast HT at
  `--threads 2`: **80.8 fps** (up from 41.7 fps in 0.10.0) measured
  against a 59.94 fps source through the offline profiler. Live
  `open_htj2k_rtp_recv --no-vsync` sustains **60.01 +/- 0.31 fps**
  locked to the source cadence over a 2000-frame soak driven from
  a real 59.94 fps sender on the camera 4K 4:2:2 1.7-bpp fixture.
  Decode time avg 13.13 ms (max 25.47 ms), **zero** decode-slot
  evictions, **zero** render-slot evictions, **zero** frame drops,
  no thermal-related drift.

## Tools
* `source/apps/rtp_recv/tools/rtp_decode_profile.cpp` - offline
  single-threaded harness that loads dumped `.j2c` codestreams and
  times `init() + parse() + invoke_line_based_stream[_reuse]()` per
  frame across a configurable number of loops. Built as
  `open_htj2k_rtp_decode_profile` when `-DOPENHTJ2K_RTP=ON`. Used
  to bound rtp_recv decode cost without the receive / socket /
  display pipeline in the way, and to dump decoded Y/Cb/Cr planes
  for byte-equality comparison between the legacy and reuse paths.
* `source/apps/rtp_recv/tools/rtp_file_replay.py` - minimal
  `.rtp` file replayer for the 16-bit-length-prefixed file format,
  with `--rate-bps` wire-rate pacing and `--start-delay` receiver
  warm-up. Complements `rtp_loopback_send.py` (single-codestream)
  and lets regression tests drive the receiver from captured
  multi-frame fixtures without a live sender.
* `source/apps/rtp_recv/tools/README.md` documents the
  dump -> replay -> profile -> perf workflow end to end.

## Bugfixes
* `j2k_main_header::read()` was `push_back`-ing COC, TLM, PLM, QCC,
  RGN, PPM, COM, DFS, and ATK marker segments into their parent
  vectors without clearing them first. Single-decoder-instance users
  were unaffected because those codepaths never iterated the
  growing lists, and users that allocated a fresh
  `openhtj2k_decoder` per frame were unaffected because the vectors
  started empty on every parse. Users that called
  `openhtj2k_decoder::init()` to re-load a new codestream into the
  same instance (as the new RTP receiver's decode worker does) saw
  the previous frame's marker segments concatenated onto the
  current frame's, which invalidated the main-header reuse
  fingerprint comparison. Clears each marker-segment vector at the
  top of `read()`. Three lines, no behavior change for single-call
  users.

# [0.10.0] - 2026-04-11

## New Features
* Experimental **RFC 9828 RTP receiver** at
  `source/apps/rtp_recv/open_htj2k_rtp_recv`, gated behind the new
  `-DOPENHTJ2K_RTP=ON` CMake option. Receives a live HTJ2K RTP stream
  over UDP, reassembles frames per RFC 9828 §5.1/§5.2, decodes through
  the line-based streaming decoder, and displays the result in a
  letterboxed GLFW window (or dumps codestreams for diagnosis).
  Default builds are unaffected; the receiver and its GLFW/OpenGL
  dependencies are only pulled in when the flag is set.
* Three-thread pipeline. A dedicated receive thread drains the UDP
  socket (non-blocking `recv` + `wait_readable` poll) and feeds a
  1-deep latest-wins decode slot. A decode thread reuses one
  long-lived `openhtj2k_decoder` via `init()` across frames, saving
  the ~14 ms `ThreadPool` spin-up per frame, and pushes results into
  a 1-deep latest-wins render slot. The main thread owns the GL
  context and does upload + draw + swap. Latest-wins semantics drop
  stale frames in favour of minimum motion-to-photon latency.
* Two color-conversion paths, both sustaining real-time 4K 4:2:2 @
  30 fps on modern x86-64:
  - `--color-path shader` (default): GL 3.3 core fragment shader
    samples three planar R8 textures (Y, Cb, Cr) and bakes the
    BT.601/709, full- or narrow-range matrix + bias + scale into
    uniforms. One vertex shader, one VAO, one fullscreen triangle
    strip; GLSL 330 programs compiled at renderer init.
  - `--color-path cpu`: AVX2 inner loop processing 8 luma pixels
    per iteration. Handles 4:4:4 and 4:2:2 / 4:2:0 chroma layouts
    via a 4-wide chroma load and `permutevar8x32` duplication;
    asymmetric ratios fall through to the existing scalar loop.
    Auto-selected when GL 3.3 core context creation fails, so
    headless and GL-incompatible environments also sustain 30 fps.
* RTP-timestamp frame pacer. Under `--no-vsync`, presentation is
  scheduled at `ref_steady_tp + (source_rtp_ts - ref_rtp_ts) / 90 kHz`
  so the render cadence follows the sender's intended cadence
  frame-for-frame and is immune to UDP burst arrival jitter. A
  runaway guard rebases the reference on decode stalls, sender
  restarts, or long pauses. `--pace-fps N` sets the fallback period
  and the runaway-guard window; `--pace-fps 0` disables the pacer.
* RFC 9828 §5.1 Main Packet and §5.2 Body Packet parser, 24-bit
  extended sequence tracking per §5.2, R=1 main-header caching,
  tail-loss detection via the RTP marker bit, and per-frame Main
  Packet metadata (TP/ORDH/R/S/C/PRIMS/TRANS/MAT/RANGE) carried
  through to the YCbCr→RGB path so §5.3 coefficients are picked
  per frame. Supports BT.601 and BT.709 in full- and narrow-range;
  BT.2020 NCL, signed components, and `C=1` code-block caching are
  not yet implemented.
* `source/apps/rtp_recv/tools/rtp_loopback_send.py` — Python helper
  that wraps a single complete codestream as one RFC 9828 Main
  Packet and sends it over UDP loopback for local regression
  testing without a live sender.
* New CLI surface: `--port`, `--bind`, `--frames`, `--no-render`,
  `--no-vsync`, `--no-decode`, `--threading {on,off}`,
  `--color-path {shader|cpu}`, `--pace-fps <N>`, `--threads <N>`,
  `--colorspace {bt709|bt601|rgb}`, `--range {full|narrow}`,
  `--dump-codestream <fmt>`, `--smoke-test`.
* `--dump-codestream` pattern strings are validated at parse time
  to contain exactly one integer conversion specifier (`%d`, `%i`,
  `%u`, `%o`, `%x`, or `%X`, with optional flags / width /
  precision). Rejects any other format directive so the snprintf
  call in the dump helper cannot be handed an unexpected specifier.

## Build
* New `-DOPENHTJ2K_RTP=ON` CMake option builds the experimental
  `open_htj2k_rtp_recv` binary. Requires GLFW 3.x development
  headers (`libglfw3-dev` on Debian/Ubuntu, `glfw-devel` on Fedora,
  `brew install glfw` on macOS) and an OpenGL 3.3 core profile
  driver at runtime. Off by default so existing builds on systems
  without a window system are unaffected.

## Documentation
* README gains three new sections covering the RTP receiver: a
  summary bullet under *What OpenHTJ2K provides*, a build
  subsection alongside the WebAssembly build, and a usage
  subsection next to the decoder one. The usage section documents
  the CLI option list, the recommended `net.core.rmem_max` sysctl
  for 4K streams, realistic hardware requirements for 4K @ 30 fps,
  and the known NVIDIA + GNOME/Mutter + Wayland + vsync issue
  (workaround: run with `--no-vsync` and rely on the RTP-timestamp
  pacer).

## Bugfixes
* `j2c_src_memory::alloc_memory`
  (`source/core/codestream/codestream_source.cpp`) was overwriting
  `buf` without freeing the previous allocation. Single-call usage
  from the `openhtj2k_decoder` constructor never tripped this
  because `buf` starts as `nullptr` from the default ctor and the
  destructor frees it once. Callers that reuse a decoder instance
  via `openhtj2k_decoder::init()` would leak ~1.7 MB per 4K frame
  — roughly 3 GB/min at 30 fps. Fixes the leak so the decoder is
  safe to reuse across frames in long-running pipelines (such as
  the new RTP receiver's long-lived decode worker).

# [0.9.1] - 2026-04-10

## Bugfixes
* Fix `Psot=0` backward EOC scan in `j2k_tile_part::read()`
  (`source/core/coding/coding_units.cpp`) stepping by 2 bytes per
  iteration instead of 1. The scan only inspected byte pairs starting
  at even offsets within the tile-part body; codestreams whose
  `0xFF 0xD9` EOC marker happened to land at an odd offset were
  silently mis-decoded, falling back to the last two bytes, then
  over-advancing the input cursor by one byte and producing
  `SOT marker segment expected but D900 is found`. Surfaced against
  real-world 4K 4:2:2 1.7-bpp broadcast HTJ2K captures where roughly
  half of all frames had an odd-offset EOC.

# [0.9.0] - 2026-04-09

## Performance
* HT block decoder: nibble-packed sigma representation for SPP/MRP passes,
  replacing byte-per-sample storage; halves memory traffic in significance
  propagation and magnitude refinement
* HT block decoder: branchless VLC unstuff eliminates short-circuit branches;
  CTZ-based SPP/MRP with branchless bit importers halve branch misses
* HT block decoder: fused dequantize pass with vectorized kappa computation
  and specialized 9/7 cascade; removes a separate dequant loop
* HT block decoder: vectorize Emax computation in cleanup decode
* AVX2: add 4-quad 16-bit decode path for HT block decoder
* AVX-512: expand coverage to FDWT vertical lifting and all color transform
  functions (forward/inverse ICT and RCT)
* AVX-512: masked stores for vertical DWT tail columns, eliminating scalar
  fallback for non-multiple-of-16 widths
* NEON: port nibble-packed sigma SPP/MRP, add irrev 5/3 (ATK) IDWT kernels
  (horizontal and vertical), add 16-bit HT cleanup decode path (pLSB > 16)
* WASM: port nibble-packed sigma SPP/MRP to WASM SIMD decoder
* Vectorize PPM interleave output (SSE4.1 / NEON) and PGM/PGX byte-packing
  in decoder CLI
* ThreadPool: lock-free `get()` via atomic index; skip pool overhead entirely
  in single-threaded mode
* ThreadPool: replace `std::queue<std::function<void()>>` with a fixed-size
  32 K-slot `InlineTask` ring buffer with cache-line aligned head/tail; eliminates
  per-task heap allocation from `std::deque` chunk management and `std::function`
  type-erased storage. 32-byte inline storage with `memcpy` fast path for
  trivially-copyable lambdas (all hot-path captures); relocate-trampoline slow
  path for non-trivial captures
* DWT batch path: eliminate per-tile per-level `Xext` / `Yext` copy buffer.
  In-place horizontal DWT now handles all rows (including the first and last
  row of each tile) by prepending `DWT_LEFT_SLACK = 8` floats and appending
  `DWT_RIGHT_SLACK = SIMD_PADDING = 32` floats of border slack to every
  `j2k_subband` / `j2k_resolution::i_samples` allocation; the user-visible
  pointer is offset by `DWT_LEFT_SLACK`. Removes a per-row `memcpy` round-trip
  for the boundary rows
* DWT: replace scalar PSE-fill loops with constant-pattern SIMD reflection
  (`vpermps` on AVX2 / AVX-512, `vrev64q` + `vextq` on NEON, `i32x4_shuffle`
  on WASM SIMD); covers `idwt_1d_row_inplace`, `idwt_1d_sr_inplace`, and
  `fdwt_1d_sr_inplace`. Drops the `PSEo()` modulo + branch on the hot path
* `coding_units`: flatten `unique_ptr<unique_ptr<T>[]>` double-indirection in
  `pband`, `subbands`, `precincts`, and `resolution` to single-allocation
  flat arrays via `operator new[]` + placement-new (matching the existing
  `j2k_codeblock` pattern). Reduces N+1 heap allocations to 1 per container
  and improves cache locality
* `coding_units`: embed `tagtree` by value in `j2k_precinct_subband`,
  eliminating two heap allocations per precinct-subband
* `decoder`: hoist per-tile scratch vectors (`band_h`, `tile_x_off`, `tile_w`,
  `row_ptrs`, `accum`) out of the multi-tile scatter loop in
  `decode_line_based_stream`; reduces O(numTiles.x × numTiles.y) heap
  allocations to a constant 5

## Bug Fixes
* Fix AVX2 `pack_i32_to_u8`: signed values were incorrectly clamped to zero
  by `packus`; now clamps via `max(0)` before packing
* Fix fused dequant SIMD overshoot race condition with branchless VLC/MEL
* Fix WASM `wasm_u16x8_shl` → `wasm_i16x8_shl` in 16-bit decode path
* Fix WASM 16-bit HT decode regression and DC level shift
* Fix intermittent DFS/ATK test failures: zero full stride×height in LL
  resolution buffer
* Fix segfault when `/dev/null` used as decoder output
* Suppress all compiler warnings in native and WASM builds
* Fix four memory leaks on exception paths: `~j2k_tile_component` now finalizes
  `line_dec` / `line_enc` so `aligned_mem_alloc`'d sub-resources are released
  even if `finalize_*()` was never called explicitly; `init_line_decode`
  validates DWT direction before allocating state arrays (fail-fast);
  `create_compressed_buffer` NULL-checks the `realloc` result instead of
  losing the original pointer; the four `decoder.cpp` `invoke` variants
  validate tile count *before* allocating raw `new int32_t[]` output buffers
  (was leaking on the validation throw)
* `coding_units`: add RAII `placement_new_array_guard<T>` and apply it at all
  five placement-new array construction sites (codeblocks, pband, subbands,
  precincts, resolution); partial construction failures now unwind cleanly
  instead of leaving the destructor calling `~T` on uninitialized memory
* ThreadPool: replace silent ring overflow under `NDEBUG` (`assert`-only) with
  a `std::runtime_error` throw in both `push_task` and `push_batch`; raise
  `RING_CAP` from 8192 to 32768 to comfortably hold the worst-case 4K-tile
  encode burst (a single precinct can enqueue ~5-8 K codeblock tasks
  back-to-back via `push_batch` before workers begin draining)

## WASM
* Node.js v24 compatibility: rewrite module loader to evaluate Emscripten JS
  as CJS via `new Function()`, pass `.wasm` binary directly via `wasmBinary`
  option, bypassing Emscripten's `fetch()`-based loader
* Add WASM CI job to GitHub Actions workflow
* Add ~137 WASM conformance tests (HT Profile 0, Profile 1, HiFi) using
  `node open_htj2k_dec.mjs` decode + native `imgcmp` comparison
* Align `index.html` ESM exports with updated wrapper API

## Build
* Add ctest cleanup fixture to remove stale test artifacts
* Polyfill `_mm256_set_m128i` in `utils.hpp` under `__GNUC__ < 10` (next to
  the existing `_mm256_storeu2_m128i` fallback). Fixes build on GCC 7.5.0
  and other older toolchains where the intrinsic was added to GCC's
  `<avxintrin.h>` only in GCC 10 (October 2019). Resolves a two-phase template
  lookup error in `ht_block_decoding.hpp` and a regular declaration error in
  `ht_block_decoding_avx2.cpp`

# [0.8.0] - 2026-04-05

## New Features
* Add JPH file format decoding with automatic colorspace detection. The decoder
  now accepts `.jph` input files, parses the JP2 box structure (signature →
  ftyp → jp2h → jp2c), extracts the embedded J2K codestream, and reads the
  `colr` box EnumCS field. When EnumCS is 18 (YCbCr) and the output is PPM,
  YCbCr→RGB conversion (BT.601) is applied automatically — no `-ycbcr` flag
  needed. The explicit `-ycbcr bt601|bt709` flag still overrides the
  auto-detected standard.
* Move JPH box parsing (`parse_jph_boxes`, `get_color_space`) into the library
  (`jph.hpp` / `jph.cpp`) and expose it via `decoder.hpp`; the app-layer
  now calls the library API instead of duplicating box-parsing logic.

## Performance
* AVX-512 IDWT: add 9 new functions (`idwt_avx512.cpp`) covering horizontal
  lifting (irrev 9/7 and rev 5/3) and vertical deinterleave / lifting steps;
  dispatched when `OPENHTJ2K_TRY_AVX2 && __AVX512F__` — falls back to AVX2
  on non-AVX-512 x86-64 CPUs with no code change required
* NEON: vextq+carry optimization for horizontal IDWT eliminates per-row
  boundary-extension copies; irrev 9/7 lossy: batch −8 %, streaming −34 %;
  rev 5/3 lossless: −10 %
* AVX2: widen HT cleanup decode MagSgn path to full 256-bit in
  `ht_cleanup_decode`, processing 8 coefficients per iteration instead of 4
* FDWT: optimize streaming cascade and `adv_step_f` to reduce per-row
  overhead; add SIMD dispatch (AVX2/NEON) for the reversible 5/3 `adv_step_f`
  vertical lifting step

## Bug Fixes
* Fix segfault on truncated JPH/J2K codestreams: guard box and marker
  parsers against premature end-of-stream
* Fix streaming decoder vertical upsampling for subsampled components
  (e.g. 4:2:0 / 4:2:2): chroma rows are now correctly replicated when the
  output stride does not match the subsampled component height
* Fix scalar color transform fallback guard: condition now matches the
  dispatch table order, preventing wrong-path selection on non-AVX2 / non-NEON
  builds

## WASM
* Vectorize fused YCbCr→RGB color transforms and interleave step in
  `color_wasm.cpp` using WASM SIMD 128-bit intrinsics; add
  `OPENHTJ2K_ENABLE_WASM_SIMD` build flags for the new translation unit
* Add YCbCr→RGB conversion (BT.601 / BT.709) to the Node.js decoder CLI
  (`open_htj2k_dec.mjs`)
* Auto-detect YCbCr colorspace from JPH inputs in `index.html`; update
  dropzone UI with JPH support note and local-decode privacy text; promote
  privacy notice to a standalone banner

# [0.7.1] - 2026-04-04

## Bugfixes
* Fix undefined behaviour in `ht_magref_decode` (scalar and NEON paths):
  left-shifting a negative `int32_t` value is UB in C++; combined into a
  single unsigned-arithmetic shift
  (`static_cast<int32_t>((0xFFFFFFFEU | ...) << pLSB)`)
* Work around clang-18 code-generation bug: clang 18 miscompiles certain
  inline functions in `coding_units.cpp` when building for AArch64 NEON,
  producing wrong decoder output. Add `-fno-inline` to `coding_units.cpp`
  when `CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER_VERSION < 19` and the compiler is Clang.
  Clang 19+, GCC, and MSVC are unaffected. All 445 conformance tests pass
  on both clang-18 and clang-20.
* Fix streaming encoder (`-i file.pgx,...`) rejecting subsampled (4:2:2,
  4:2:0, etc.) PGX inputs. `PgxStreamReader` now accepts component files
  whose dimensions are integer sub-multiples of the luma component, computes
  the correct XRsiz/YRsiz factors for the SIZ marker, seeks each chroma file
  to the correct row (`y / YRsiz`), and skips redundant `push_line_enc` calls
  for chroma on luma rows that carry no new chroma data.

# [0.7.0] - 2026-04-04

## JPEG 2000 Part 2: DFS and ATK kernel support
* Add encoder and decoder support for Part 2 Downsampling Factor Structures
  (DFS) markers
* Add decoder support for arbitrary ATK (Arbitrary Transform Kernel) DWT
  kernels: irreversible 9/7-based and reversible 5/3-based ATK
* Add scalar FDWT and AVX2 IDWT implementations for ATK kernels
* Add 5 conformance test cases for Part 2 DFS+ATK bitstreams (all pass)
* Fix AVX2 dequantize: use `transformation == 1` (not truthy) to distinguish
  lossless from ATK kernels (`transformation >= 2` is lossy but truthy)
* Fix ATK finalize downshift: `(transformation==1)?0:FRACBITS-bitdepth`
* Fix bounds-safe color transform dispatch for ATK (`transformation >= 2`)
* Fix LL0 subband dimensions for DFS codestreams in streaming decode
* Fix ATK encode OOB color dispatch; add line-based DFS/ATK tests

## Decoder
* `-reduce` now respects DFS markers: the maximum reduce level is clamped to
  the number of consecutive bidirectional DWT levels, preventing nonsensical
  HONLY/VONLY reduced-resolution outputs
* Fix PPM output for subsampled (4:2:2) codestreams: the streaming path
  correctly upsamples chroma with nearest-neighbour interpolation; the batch
  `write_ppm` path uses a scalar fallback for mismatched component dimensions
* Add experimental `-ycbcr bt601|bt709` flag: converts YCbCr to RGB during
  PPM output using full-range ITU-R BT.601 or BT.709 coefficients
  (fixed-point 2^14); handles 4:2:2 nearest-neighbour chroma upsampling;
  applies to PPM output only

## Encoder
* Fix streaming (line-based) path for PGX input: a new `PgxStreamReader`
  opens one file per component and reads rows on demand; previously PGX input
  always triggered "Failed to open input file for streaming"

## WASM
* Fix 4:2:2 chroma subsampling in `invoke_decoder_to_rgba()` WASM wrapper
* Add YCbCr→RGB conversion buttons (BT.601 / BT.709) to the web demo at
  https://htj2k-demo.pages.dev/
* Modernize button styling in the web demo

# [0.6.0] - 2026-04-02

## WASM
* Add `invoke_decoder_stream()` C export: streaming line-based decode via
  callback, eliminating the 96 MB W×H×C int32 output buffer entirely
* Add `invoke_decoder_to_rgba()` C export: converts decoded samples to a
  packed uint8/uint16 big-endian buffer inside WASM, eliminating the JS
  per-sample pixel loop
* Add `open_htj2k_dec.mjs`: Node.js CLI decoder built on the WASM library;
  supports J2C / J2K / JPH input, PGM / PPM / PGX output, `--reduce`,
  `--num_threads`, and `--iter` options
* Fix WASM SIMD build: add `-O3 -flto` to SIMD object compilation
* Fix `open_htj2k_dec.mjs`: compute correct output dimensions when `--reduce` > 0
* Update `index.html` to use the new streaming and RGBA export APIs

## Performance (native)
* Fused MCT + finalize: color inverse transform and int32 output writeback
  combined into a single pass, eliminating an intermediate float buffer
* In-place horizontal IDWT: eliminates ext_buf memcpy per row
* NEON: port lossy dequantize fast path; fix color_neon build failure
* NEON: 2× unroll `idwt_level_src_fn` interleave loop
* IDWT cascade: eliminate redundant `get_dl` / `is_lp` calls in hot loop
* AlignedLargePool: extend macOS support; route file I/O buffers through pool
* Stack-allocate Eline / rholine scratch arrays; route large buffers through
  AlignedLargePool to reduce heap fragmentation
* Use aligned AVX2 loads (`_mm256_load_ps`) where 32-byte alignment is
  guaranteed, replacing unaligned variants in hot DWT paths

## Portability
* Lower minimum compiler requirement from C++17 to C++11
* Replace all `[[nodiscard]]` / `[[maybe_unused]]` raw attributes with
  `OPENHTJ2K_NODISCARD` / `OPENHTJ2K_MAYBE_UNUSED` macros that expand
  to the real attributes under C++17 and to nothing under C++14/11
* Replace `if constexpr` with plain `if` in HT block decoding (all four
  variants: generic, AVX2, NEON, WASM)
* ThreadPool: split pre-C++17 `enqueue()` into separate C++14 and C++11
  branches using `std::decay_t` and `typename std::decay<T>::type`
  respectively
* Remove pre-existing malformed `#define[[maybe_unsed]]` line in utils.hpp
* All three standard levels (C++11, C++14, C++17) verified: clean build
  and 277/277 conformance tests pass under each

## Documentation
* README: expand Requirements section with per-standard compatibility table
* README: document `open_htj2k_dec.mjs` build and usage

# [0.5.1] - 2026-04-01

 ## WASM SIMD
 * Add color transform vectorization: new color_wasm.cpp with all 8
   color transform functions (forward/inverse RCT and ICT, integer and
   float-domain variants) implemented using WASM SIMD 128-bit intrinsics,
   processing 4 elements per iteration

# [0.5.0] - 2026-04-01

 ## WASM SIMD
 * Complete separation of WASM-SIMD from NEON: dedicated source files
   (fdwt_wasm.cpp, idwt_wasm.cpp, ht_block_encoding_wasm.cpp,
   ht_block_decoding_wasm.cpp) guarded solely by
   OPENHTJ2K_ENABLE_WASM_SIMD; no NEON flag is used in WASM builds
 * Translate HT block encoding and decoding to native WASM-SIMD intrinsics
   (v128_t); encoder state classes in ht_block_encoding_wasm.hpp
 * Add dedicated WASM fwd_buf<X> implementation in ht_block_decoding.hpp
 * subprojects/CMakeLists.txt: compile library twice — scalar build
   linked to libopen_htj2k.js, SIMD build linked to libopen_htj2k_simd.js

 ## Performance
 * IDWT: eliminate redundant memcpy in idwt_level_src_fn; remove hp_tmp
   scratch buffer; reduce streaming ring buffer depth from 12 to 8
 * IDWT: vectorize LP/HP interleave with AVX2 (unpacklo/hi + permute2f128)
   and NEON; vectorize 5/3 reversible vertical lifting steps with AVX2
 * FDWT/IDWT: AVX2 and NEON odd-width interleave/deinterleave fixes
 * Decoder finalization: AVX2 and NEON paths for float→int32 conversion
   in decode_line_based_stream; NEON ds==0 fast path; 16-element/iter loop
 * NEON: 2× unroll reversible vertical lifting steps and FDWT deinterleave
 * DWT cascade: specialize 5/3 path; fix O(n²) scan-window growth
 * HT block decoding: skip sigma stores for single-pass codeblocks;
   skip redundant memset for single-pass codeblocks
 * Allocation: eliminate per-codeblock allocation storm in
   j2k_precinct_subband; replace per-strip and per-resolution allocation;
   hoist tree_path vector out of per-codeblock loop; replace per-block
   all_segments std::vector with stack array in htj2k_decode()
 * ThreadPool: batch-push tasks, reserve marker list, combine ring buffer
   and predecoded pool; pre-fault ring/prefetch buffers; reduce
   task-queue thundering herd
 * LB encoder: overlap DWT computation with HT block encoding
 * Eliminate bulk ring_buf/prefetch_buf zeroing; zero only empty regions
 * Replace scratch array memset with per-row 8-byte guard zeros

 ## Fixes
 * Fix O(n²) scan window growth in DWT cascade 5/3 specialization
 * Add <utility> include for std::swap in fdwt.cpp and idwt.cpp

# [0.4.1] - 2026-03-30

* Introduce a temporary workaround for the line-based validation test in Windows ARM64.

# [0.4.0] - 2026-03-30

## New APIs
* Add `invoke_line_based()` decoder API: row-by-row output via callback
  using per-subband ring buffers; avoids full-image intermediate allocation
* Add `invoke_line_based_stream()` decoder API: multi-tile scatter path
  assembling full-width output rows from per-tile strip buffers
* Add `encode_line_based_stream()` encoder API: push-row streaming encoder
  driven by a user-supplied source callback
* Add `lb_compare` utility to validate line-based output against `invoke()`

## Architecture
* Change `sprec_t` from `int32_t` to `float`: DWT pipeline now operates
  natively in float32, eliminating integer↔float round-trip conversions
* `fdwt_2d_state` / `idwt_2d_state`: new stateful streaming DWT classes
  that process one row at a time for the line-based encode/decode paths
* Line-based mode is now the default for encoder and decoder apps;
  the previous full-image (batch) path is selected with the `-batch` flag

## Performance
* AVX2 horizontal DWT: 2× loop unrolling on all lifting step loops
* NEON: full float32 horizontal and vertical DWT kernels
* ICT/RCT color transforms: AVX2 and NEON variants with runtime dispatch
* LB decoder: pipeline MCT+clamp of row Y with pool pull of row Y+1,
  achieving 18–23 % throughput improvement at T≥4 threads
* Encoder: per-thread `cblk_data_pool` bump allocator replaces per-block
  `malloc`/`free` in the HT block coding hot path; PSE scratch buffer hoisted out
  of per-tile DWT calls

## Build / Tests
* Decoder and encoder apps reject unknown command-line flag names
* Introduce `OPENHTJ2K_EXPORT` macro, removing duplicated `__declspec`
  guards from `encoder.hpp`
* Add `lb_stream_validation.cmake`: conformance tests for
  `invoke_line_based_stream()` across all HT profile-0/1 and HF bitstreams
* Remove redundant `lb_*` cmake test files (duplicate of non-lb equivalents);
  CTest count reduced from 480 to 277
* WASM: dark UI redesign, SIMD badge, decode-time display, GitHub link

